{"title_page": "Gideon Yu", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Gideon Yu\n| image       = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1971|5|14|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Seoul, South Korea]]\n| education   = [[University School of Nashville]]<br>[[Stanford University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]]) <br>[[Harvard Business School]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n| occupation  = President & co-owner of the [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n| spouse      =  Susie Yu (korean:\ubbfc\ud61c\uc815)\n| children    = Jonathan and Emily\n}}\n\n'''Gideon Lee Yu''' (born May 14, 1971)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://birthdatabase.com|title=Free Birthday Database|website=birthdatabase.com|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> is a Korean-American sports executive and a high technology investor and advisor.\n\nYu is currently the co-owner of the [[San Francisco 49ers]] football team. He was previously the team president.<ref name=mnews_49ers>{{cite web|last=Kawakami|first=Tim|title=49ers add former Facebook exec Gideon Yu: Is there more to this?|url=http://blogs.mercurynews.com/kawakami/2011/04/26/49ers-hire-former-facebook-exec-gideon-yu-is-there-more-to-this/|work=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=29 June 2011}}</ref>  In 2012, Yu became the first president of color in the history of the [[National Football League]].<ref name=\"NFL scores A for racial hiring\">[http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9863217/nfl-gets-grade-racial-hiring-study-says NFL scores A for racial hiring].  ''ESPN'', October 22, 2013</ref> Prior to his career in professional sports management, Yu was a high-technology executive, most notably as the chief financial officer of both [[Facebook]]<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118531562451376785 Facebook Hires Gideon Yu as Chief Financial Officer].  ''Wall Street Journal'', July 25, 2007</ref> and [[YouTube]]<ref name=\"thestreet.com\">[http://www.thestreet.com/story/10307019/1/youtube-hires-yahoo-treasurer.html YouTube Hires Yahoo! Treasurer].  TheStreet.com, September 3, 2006</ref> as well as the senior vice president and treasurer of [[Yahoo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shareholder.com/visitors/dynamicdoc/document.cfm?CompanyID=YHOO&documentID=1183&PIN=&resizeThree=no&Scale=100&Keyword=Type+Keywords+Here&Page=116|title=2005 Annual Report|website=Shareholder.com|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nYu graduated from the [[University School of Nashville]] in 1989, where he was Student Body President and participated in Science Olympiad. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usn.org/page/news-detail?pk=582236|title=Convocation a Night to Remember|website=University School of Nashville|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> He then attended [[Stanford University]], majoring in [[Industrial Engineering]] and Engineering Management and received his [[MBA]] from [[Harvard Business School]]. In 1989, he received the First Place Grand Award in Environmental Science at the 40th International Science and Engineering Fair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=21947594&privcapId=81834761&previousCapId=25183454&previousTitle=Meebo,+Inc.|title=Gideon Yu: Executive Profile & Biography \u2013 Bloomberg|website=investing.businessweek.com|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn his time with the 49ers, Yu led the team's efforts in financing [[Levi's Stadium]], including securing an $850 million stadium construction loan, the largest ever in professional sports, a $200 million financing package from the NFL and the largest long-term stadium financing in NFL history. Yu also directed the 49ers drive to accelerate the opening date of Levi's Stadium from the 2015 to 2014 season.<ref>[http://www.49ers.com/team/staff/gideon-yu/550b12f9-f78c-431a-a231-fcbf54ff5972 San Francisco 49ers Front Office Staff].  ''49ers.com''</ref>  Perhaps the most notable distinction during Yu's tenure at the [[San Francisco 49ers]], however, is that he is the first president of color of any team in the history of the [[National Football League]].<ref name=\"NFL scores A for racial hiring\"/>\n\nPrior to joining the San Francisco 49ers football team, Yu was a [[General Partner]] at [[Khosla Ventures]],<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/01/business/01khosla.html Khosla Ventures raises $1b+ and hires Gideon Yu as Partner]. ''New York Times'', August 31, 2009</ref> where he led the firm's investment in [[Square (application)|Square]] and was the founding outside board member (Yu's board seat was later transferred to [[Vinod Khosla]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciol.com/News/Executive-Track/News-Reports/Vinod-Khosla-joins-Square-board/150926/0/|title=Vinod Khosla Succeeds Gideon Yu as Board Member of Square|website=Ciol.com|accessdate=23 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127230239/http://www.ciol.com/News/Executive-Track/News-Reports/Vinod-Khosla-joins-Square-board/150926/0/|archive-date=27 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nPreviously, Yu was the [[chief financial officer]] of [[Facebook]].<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118531562451376785 Facebook Hires Yu as Chief Financial Officer].  ''Wall Street Journal'', July 25, 2007</ref> Upon Yu's hiring, Facebook's founder, Mark Zuckerberg, speaking with the Wall Street Journal, said: \"I consider it kind of a coup that we were able to recruit him here.\u201d<ref name=\"Delaney\">{{cite web|last=Delaney|first=Kevin|title=Facebook Hires Yu as Finance Chief|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118531562451376785|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=25 July 2007|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Yu led the $375 million investment round<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/25/technology/24cnd-facebook.html Microsoft Invests $240 million in Facebook at a $15 billion valuation].  ''New York Times'', October 25, 2007</ref> from [[Microsoft]] and Hong-Kong billionaire [[Li Ka Shing]]<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/technologyNews/idUSN2731908420080328 Li Ka Shing Invests $120 million in Facebook at a $15 billion valuation].  Reuters, March 27, 2008</ref> at a then record $15 billion valuation. Zuckerberg further noted to the Wall Street Journal about Yu, \u201cHe's just excellent.\u201d<ref name=\"Delaney\"/> \n\nBefore Facebook, Yu was a partner at [[Sequoia Capital]],<ref>[https://venturebeat.com/2007/04/23/roundup-yus-wild-ride-stumbleupon-dot-bomb-travails-and-more/ Gideon Yu becomes a Partner at Sequoia Capital].  VentureBeat, April 23, 2007</ref> and was also the chief financial officer at [[YouTube]]<ref name=\"thestreet.com\"/> where he negotiated<ref>[http://valleywag.gawker.com/304104/how-a-cop-almost-kiboshed-the-google+youtube-deal How the Google \u2013 YouTube Deal was signed] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615035405/http://valleywag.gawker.com/304104/how-a-cop-almost-kiboshed-the-google+youtube-deal |date=June 15, 2009 }}.  Gawker, September 27, 2007</ref> its $1.65 billion sale<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/2006/10/09/technology/googleyoutube_deal/index.htm Google Buys YouTube for $1.65 billion].  CNNMoney, October 9, 2006</ref> to [[Google]] amidst a competitive auction for the company.\n\nPrior to YouTube, Yu was the [[treasurer]] and senior vice president of Finance for [[Yahoo]]<ref>[http://www.shareholder.com/visitors/dynamicdoc/document.cfm?CompanyID=YHOO&documentID=1183&PIN=&resizeThree=no&Scale=100&Keyword=Type%20Keywords%20Here&Page=116 Yahoo Corporate Officers].  Yahoo 2005 Annual Report</ref> where he executed over 30 acquisitions/investments for Yahoo, including [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]], [[Taobao]], [[Overture Services|Overture]], [[Inktomi (company)|Inktomi]], [[Flickr]], [[del.icio.us]] and over $5 billion of capital markets transactions. Prior to Yahoo, Yu was the chief financial officer of NightFire Software (acquired by [[NeuStar]], NYSE: NSR) and held positions at [[Disney]], [[Hilton Worldwide|Hilton]], and [[Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette|DLJ]] / [[CSFB]].\n\n==Philanthropy==\nYu serves on the board of trustees of the [[Monterey Bay Aquarium]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.montereybayaquarium.org/about/our-mission-and-leadership|title=Monterey Bay Aquarium Mission and Leadership|website=Montereybayaquarium.org|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> and the board of directors of [[Tipping Point Community]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tippingpoint.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=60&Itemid=58|title=Tipping Point Community|website=Tipping Point Community|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> Yu is also active philanthropically at his alma mater, [[Stanford University]], where he \"made a significant commitment to undergraduate scholarships\" and \"is volunteering as a member of the School of Engineering Advisory Council and the School of Earth Sciences Task Force.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://giving.stanford.edu/stanford-benefactor/stories/yu-scholarships|title=49ers Co-Owner Gives Back|date=12 September 2014|website=Giving.stanford.edu|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> He previously served on the boards of directors of the [[UCSF]] Medical Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.ucsf.edu/ucsf-foundation/board-directors|title=Homepage|website=Giving to UCSF|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> and BUILD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://build.org/browse/board-of-directors-and-local-advisory-boards|title=BUILD Board of Directors|website=Build.org|accessdate=23 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707061803/http://www.build.org/browse/board-of-directors-and-local-advisory-boards|archive-date=7 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://blogs.forbes.com/oliverchiang/2010/11/20/names-you-need-to-know-in-2011-the-facebook-keiretsu/ 2011 \"Forbes\" Names You Need to Know]\n*[http://www.businessinsider.com/the-silicon-valley-100-1-100-2012-1 The 2012 Silicon Valley 100]\n*[http://www.treasuryandrisk.com/Issues/2003/November%202003/Pages/40-Under-40.aspx Yu Among ''Treasury & Risk Magazine's'' 40 under 40]\n*[http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2008/fortune/0801/gallery.BestCo_ex_Googlers.fortune/3.html ''Fortune'' article on former Google employees]\n\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n{{NFLPresidents}}\n{{San Francisco 49ers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yu, Gideon}}\n[[Category:Google employees]]\n[[Category:Facebook employees]]\n[[Category:Yahoo! employees]]\n[[Category:Private equity and venture capital investors]]\n[[Category:Venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:American people of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:American chief financial officers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Gideon Yu\n| image       = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1971|5|14|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Seoul, South Korea]]\n| education   = [[University School of Nashville]]<br>[[Stanford University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]]) <br>[[Harvard Business School]] ([[Masters of Business Administration|MBA]])\n| occupation  = President & Co-Owner of the [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n| spouse      =  Susie Yu (korean:\ubbfc\ud61c\uc815)\n| children    = Jonathan and Emily\n}}\n\n'''Gideon Lee Yu''' (born May 14, 1971)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://birthdatabase.com|title=Free Birthday Database|website=birthdatabase.com|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> is a Korean-American sports executive and a high technology investor and advisor.\n\nYu is currently the co-owner of the [[San Francisco 49ers]] football team. He was previously the team president.<ref name=mnews_49ers>{{cite web|last=Kawakami|first=Tim|title=49ers add former Facebook exec Gideon Yu: Is there more to this?|url=http://blogs.mercurynews.com/kawakami/2011/04/26/49ers-hire-former-facebook-exec-gideon-yu-is-there-more-to-this/|work=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=29 June 2011}}</ref>  In 2012, Yu became the first president of color in the history of the [[National Football League]].<ref name=\"NFL scores A for racial hiring\">[http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9863217/nfl-gets-grade-racial-hiring-study-says NFL scores A for racial hiring].  ''ESPN'', October 22, 2013</ref> Prior to his career in professional sports management, Yu was a high-technology executive, most notably as the chief financial officer of both [[Facebook]]<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118531562451376785 Facebook Hires Gideon Yu as Chief Financial Officer].  ''Wall Street Journal'', July 25, 2007</ref> and [[YouTube]]<ref name=\"thestreet.com\">[http://www.thestreet.com/story/10307019/1/youtube-hires-yahoo-treasurer.html YouTube Hires Yahoo! Treasurer].  TheStreet.com, September 3, 2006</ref> as well as the senior vice president and treasurer of [[Yahoo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shareholder.com/visitors/dynamicdoc/document.cfm?CompanyID=YHOO&documentID=1183&PIN=&resizeThree=no&Scale=100&Keyword=Type+Keywords+Here&Page=116|title=2005 Annual Report|website=Shareholder.com|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nYu graduated from the [[University School of Nashville]] in 1989, where he was Student Body President and participated in Science Olympiad. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usn.org/page/news-detail?pk=582236|title=Convocation a Night to Remember|website=University School of Nashville|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> He then attended [[Stanford University]], majoring in [[Industrial Engineering]] and Engineering Management and received his [[MBA]] from [[Harvard Business School]]. In 1989, he received the First Place Grand Award in Environmental Science at the 40th International Science and Engineering Fair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=21947594&privcapId=81834761&previousCapId=25183454&previousTitle=Meebo,+Inc.|title=Gideon Yu: Executive Profile & Biography \u2013 Bloomberg|website=investing.businessweek.com|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn his time with the 49ers, Yu led the team's efforts in financing [[Levi's Stadium]], including securing an $850 million stadium construction loan, the largest ever in professional sports, a $200 million financing package from the NFL and the largest long-term stadium financing in NFL history. Yu also directed the 49ers drive to accelerate the opening date of Levi's Stadium from the 2015 to 2014 season.<ref>[http://www.49ers.com/team/staff/gideon-yu/550b12f9-f78c-431a-a231-fcbf54ff5972 San Francisco 49ers Front Office Staff].  ''49ers.com''</ref>  Perhaps the most notable distinction during Yu's tenure at the [[San Francisco 49ers]], however, is that he is the first president of color of any team in the history of the [[National Football League]].<ref name=\"NFL scores A for racial hiring\"/>\n\nPrior to joining the San Francisco 49ers football team, Yu was a [[General Partner]] at [[Khosla Ventures]],<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/01/business/01khosla.html Khosla Ventures raises $1b+ and hires Gideon Yu as Partner]. ''New York Times'', August 31, 2009</ref> where he led the firm's investment in [[Square (application)|Square]] and was the founding outside board member (Yu's board seat was later transferred to [[Vinod Khosla]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciol.com/News/Executive-Track/News-Reports/Vinod-Khosla-joins-Square-board/150926/0/|title=Vinod Khosla Succeeds Gideon Yu as Board Member of Square|website=Ciol.com|accessdate=23 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127230239/http://www.ciol.com/News/Executive-Track/News-Reports/Vinod-Khosla-joins-Square-board/150926/0/|archive-date=27 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nPreviously, Yu was the [[chief financial officer]] of [[Facebook]].<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118531562451376785 Facebook Hires Yu as Chief Financial Officer].  ''Wall Street Journal'', July 25, 2007</ref> Upon Yu's hiring, Facebook's founder, Mark Zuckerberg, speaking with the Wall Street Journal, said: \"I consider it kind of a coup that we were able to recruit him here.\u201d<ref name=\"Delaney\">{{cite web|last=Delaney|first=Kevin|title=Facebook Hires Yu as Finance Chief|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118531562451376785|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=25 July 2007|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Yu led the $375 million investment round<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/25/technology/24cnd-facebook.html Microsoft Invests $240 million in Facebook at a $15 billion valuation].  ''New York Times'', October 25, 2007</ref> from [[Microsoft]] and Hong-Kong billionaire [[Li Ka Shing]]<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/technologyNews/idUSN2731908420080328 Li Ka Shing Invests $120 million in Facebook at a $15 billion valuation].  Reuters, March 27, 2008</ref> at a then record $15 billion valuation. Zuckerberg further noted to the Wall Street Journal about Yu, \u201cHe's just excellent.\u201d<ref name=\"Delaney\"/> \n\nBefore Facebook, Yu was a partner at [[Sequoia Capital]],<ref>[https://venturebeat.com/2007/04/23/roundup-yus-wild-ride-stumbleupon-dot-bomb-travails-and-more/ Gideon Yu becomes a Partner at Sequoia Capital].  VentureBeat, April 23, 2007</ref> and was also the chief financial officer at [[YouTube]]<ref name=\"thestreet.com\"/> where he negotiated<ref>[http://valleywag.gawker.com/304104/how-a-cop-almost-kiboshed-the-google+youtube-deal How the Google \u2013 YouTube Deal was signed] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615035405/http://valleywag.gawker.com/304104/how-a-cop-almost-kiboshed-the-google+youtube-deal |date=June 15, 2009 }}.  Gawker, September 27, 2007</ref> its $1.65 billion sale<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/2006/10/09/technology/googleyoutube_deal/index.htm Google Buys YouTube for $1.65 billion].  CNNMoney, October 9, 2006</ref> to [[Google]] amidst a competitive auction for the company.\n\nPrior to YouTube, Yu was the [[treasurer]] and senior vice president of Finance for [[Yahoo]]<ref>[http://www.shareholder.com/visitors/dynamicdoc/document.cfm?CompanyID=YHOO&documentID=1183&PIN=&resizeThree=no&Scale=100&Keyword=Type%20Keywords%20Here&Page=116 Yahoo Corporate Officers].  Yahoo 2005 Annual Report</ref> where he executed over 30 acquisitions/investments for Yahoo, including [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]], [[Taobao]], [[Overture Services|Overture]], [[Inktomi (company)|Inktomi]], [[Flickr]], [[del.icio.us]] and over $5 billion of capital markets transactions. Prior to Yahoo, Yu was the chief financial officer of NightFire Software (acquired by [[NeuStar]], NYSE: NSR) and held positions at [[Disney]], [[Hilton Worldwide|Hilton]], and [[Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette|DLJ]] / [[CSFB]].\n\n==Philanthropy==\nYu serves on the board of trustees of the [[Monterey Bay Aquarium]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.montereybayaquarium.org/about/our-mission-and-leadership|title=Monterey Bay Aquarium Mission and Leadership|website=Montereybayaquarium.org|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> and the board of directors of [[Tipping Point Community]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tippingpoint.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=60&Itemid=58|title=Tipping Point Community|website=Tipping Point Community|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> Yu is also active philanthropically at his alma mater, [[Stanford University]], where he \"made a significant commitment to undergraduate scholarships\" and \"is volunteering as a member of the School of Engineering Advisory Council and the School of Earth Sciences Task Force.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://giving.stanford.edu/stanford-benefactor/stories/yu-scholarships|title=49ers Co-Owner Gives Back|date=12 September 2014|website=Giving.stanford.edu|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> He previously served on the boards of directors of the [[UCSF]] Medical Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.ucsf.edu/ucsf-foundation/board-directors|title=Homepage|website=Giving to UCSF|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> and BUILD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://build.org/browse/board-of-directors-and-local-advisory-boards|title=BUILD Board of Directors|website=Build.org|accessdate=23 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707061803/http://www.build.org/browse/board-of-directors-and-local-advisory-boards|archive-date=7 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://blogs.forbes.com/oliverchiang/2010/11/20/names-you-need-to-know-in-2011-the-facebook-keiretsu/ 2011 \"Forbes\" Names You Need to Know]\n*[http://www.businessinsider.com/the-silicon-valley-100-1-100-2012-1 The 2012 Silicon Valley 100]\n*[http://www.treasuryandrisk.com/Issues/2003/November%202003/Pages/40-Under-40.aspx Yu Among ''Treasury & Risk Magazine's'' 40 under 40]\n*[http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2008/fortune/0801/gallery.BestCo_ex_Googlers.fortune/3.html ''Fortune'' article on former Google employees]\n\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n{{NFLPresidents}}\n{{San Francisco 49ers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yu, Gideon}}\n[[Category:Google employees]]\n[[Category:Facebook employees]]\n[[Category:Yahoo! employees]]\n[[Category:Private equity and venture capital investors]]\n[[Category:Venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:American people of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:American chief financial officers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp, cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gideon_Yu"}
{"title_page": "Alexander J. Dessler", "text_new": "{{short description|American astrophysicist (b. 1928)}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Alexander J. Dessler\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1928|10|21}}\n| birth_place       = [[San Francisco, California]] United States\n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       =  USA\n| fields            = [[Magnetospheric Physics]], [[Heliophysics]], Jovian Physics\n| workplaces        = [[Lockheed Missiles and Space Company]], <br/>[[Rice University]],<br/>[[Lunar and Planetary Laboratory]], [[University of Arizona]] <br/>[[Texas A & M University]]\n| alma_mater        = [[California Institute of Technology]],<br/>[[Duke University]]\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = 1956\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[William M. Fairbank]]\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = Arthur A. Few; Thomas W. Hill; David Cummings, David Criswell, William Sorenson, Milo Schield, Henry B. Garrett, Steve Bowling, Yong Yang, Jie Zhan\n| notable_students  = Arthur A. Few; Thomas W. Hill; David Cummings; Henry B. Garrett\n| known_for         = Earth's Magnetosphere; Jupiter's Magnetosphere; Founding Chairman of the Department of Space Science, [[Rice University]].\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = Macelwane Medal; Fleming Medal, [[Arctowski Medal]]\n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = Lorraine Barbara Dessler\n| module      = \n}}\n\n'''Alexander J. Dessler''',  born October 21, 1928, in San Francisco, California, is a [[space scientist]] known for conceiving the term [[heliosphere]].<ref name=\"TAMU Adj.Page\">{{cite web |last1=Dessler |first1=Alexander J. |title=Biographical Sketch |url=https://atmo.tamu.edu/people/profiles/adjunct-faculty/dessleralex.html |website=AJD, CV |publisher=Texas A&M University Atmospheric Sciences |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Solar Wind article\">{{cite journal |last1=Dessler |first1=A. J. |title=Solar wind and interplanetary magnetic field |journal=Reviews of Geophysics |date=February 1967 |volume=5 |issue=1 |page=1-41 |doi=10.1029/RG005i001p00001 |url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/RG005i001p00001 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and Education==\nDessler received a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] in [[Physics]] from the [[California Institute of Technology]] in 1952 and a [[Ph.D]] in Physics from [[Duke University]] in 1956.<ref name=\"TAMU Adj.Page\" /><ref name=\"Duke Alumni\">{{cite web |title=Dept. of Physics Alumni |url=https://phy.duke.edu/alumni/alexander-j-dessler |website=Dept. of Physics Alumni |publisher=Duke University Trinity College of Arts and Sciences |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDessler began his career at [[Lockheed Missiles and Space Company]]. In 1963, while at the [[Southwest Center for Advanced Studies]], now [[University of Texas at Dallas]], he was recruited by Rice University president [[Kenneth S. Pitzer]] to found the world's first university \"Space Science\" department, as a response to [[John F. Kennedy|President John F. Kennedy's]] [[Address at Rice University on the Nation's Space Effort|Moon Speech]], delivered at Rice on September 12, 1962.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dick |first1=Steven J. |last2=Launius |first2=Roger D. |title=Societal Impact of Spaceflight |date=2007 |publisher=National aeronautics and Space administration Office of External Relations History Division |location=Washington D.C. |isbn=978-0-16-080190-7 |page=456..458 |url=https://history.nasa.gov/sp4801-chapter23.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Reiff |first1=Patricia |title=About Space Science at Rice University |url=http://space.rice.edu/alumni/about.html |website=About Space Science at Rice University |publisher=Rice Space Institute |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe is [[emeritus professor]] of [[Space physics|Space Physics]] and [[Astronomy]] at Rice University, active from 1963 to 1992. His research subject areas are [[magnetospheric physics]], planetary magnetospheres, primarily of [[magnetosphere of Jupiter|Jupiter]] and [[planetary science]].  He was founding chair of the Department of Space Science at Rice University, later known as the Department of Space Physics and Astronomy.<ref name=\"NYT Alfven\">{{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=Walter |title=Hannes Alfven, 86, Founder Of Field in Physics, Is Dead |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/05/obituaries/hannes-alfven-86-founder-of-field-in-physics-is-dead.html?searchResultPosition=2 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |issue=Section B Pg. 22 |publisher=New York Times |date=5 April 1995}}</ref>\nDessler served three terms as chair of the department and retired in 1992.<ref name=\"Space Science Bldg. 1965\">{{cite web |title=Space Science Building, 1965 |url=https://ricehistorycorner.com/2011/09/29/space-science-building-1965/ |website=Rice History Corner |publisher=Rice University}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Dick |first1=Steven J. |last2=Launius |first2=Roger D. |title=Societal Impact of Spaceflight |date=2007 |publisher=National aeronautics and Space administration Office of External Relations History Division |location=Washington D.C. |isbn=978-0-16-080190-7 |page=456..458 |url=https://history.nasa.gov/sp4801-chapter23.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Dessler became Senior Research Scientist at the Lunar and Planetary Laboratory, [[University of Arizona]], until 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boyd |first1=Jade |title=Rice space physics pioneer recognized by National Academy |url=https://news.rice.edu/2015/01/26/rice-space-physics-pioneer-recognized-by-national-academy/ |website=Rice News and Media |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> He is retired and an adjunct professor of Space Physics at Texas A & M University.<ref>{{cite web |title=Adjunct and Emeritus Faculty |url=https://atmo.tamu.edu/people/profiles/adjunct-faculty/dessleralex.html |website=Adjunct and Emeritus Faculty |publisher=Texas A&M Atmospheric Sciences |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Space Science Bldg. 1965\" />  \n\nAt the ''Possible Relationships Between Solar Activity and Meteorological Phenomena'' symposium, [[Goddard Space Flight Center]], November 7-8, 1973, [[Charles Greely Abbot|Charles Greely Abbot's]] lifelong work on solar activity provided the foundation for research as a possible driver for Earth [[weather]]. In addressing the topic, A. J. Dessler commented that any increased energy received in Earth's [[troposphere]] due to increased solar activity is negligible, and that correlations alone do not establish causation. The challenges facing scientists with complex systems like the planet's weather require finding a coupling mechanism. He suggested to continue seeking physical mechanisms.<ref name=\"Solar Activity and Earth Weather\">{{cite web |last1=Bendeen |first1=William R. |last2=Maran |first2=Stephen P. |title=POSSIBLE RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN SOLAR ACTIVITY AND METEOROLOGICAL PHENOMENA |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19760007440.pdf |website=NRTS NASA |publisher=NASA Goddard Space Flight Center |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Dressler refuted the proposition put forth by retired [[NASA]] scientist [[Addison Bain]] concerning the causes and combustion of the [[Hindenburg disaster]]. Dessler described Bain's incendiary paint theory as flawed science based on the [[stoichiometry]] of the coating's composition, the very slow burn rate of the metallic coating of the airship, and the lack of a high enough energy source to ignite the coating.<ref name=\"Hindenburg Paint Refutation\">{{cite web |last1=Dessler |first1=A. J. |title=The Hindenburg hydrogen fire: Fatal flaws in the Addison Bain incendiary paint theory |url=http://spot.colorado.edu/%E2%88%BCdziadeck/zf/LZ129fire.pdf |publisher=University of Colorado at Boulder |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ChemMatters Hindenburg Article\">{{cite web |last1=Graham |first1=Tim |title=Hindenburg: Formula for Disaster |url=chemmatters-dec2007-hindenburg (5).pdf |website=CemMatters |publisher=acs.org |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDessler and his wife Lorraine have four children, including Texas A & M atmospheric scientist [[Andrew Dessler]].\n\n==Awards and honors==\n*1963 - [[American Geophysical Union]] [[James B. Macelwane Medal|Macelwane Medal]].<ref name=Macelwane> {{cite web|title=AJ Dessler Macelwane |url=https://www.agu.org/Honor-and-Recognize/Honors/Union-Medals/James-B-Macelwane-Medal|publisher=[[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU)}}</ref>  This also was the occasion of being named Fellow of the American Geophysical Union<ref name=\"AGU Fellow\">{{cite web |title=Honors Fellows |url=https://honors.agu.org/honorsfellow/1599-dessler/ |website=AGU Fellows |publisher=AGU |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*1993 - American Geophysical Union, John Adam Fleming Medal Winner<ref name=\"John Adam Fleming Medal\">{{cite web |title=John Adam Fleming Medal |url=https://www.agu.org/Honor-and-Recognize/Honors/Union-Medals/John-Adam-Fleming-Medal |website=AGU John Adam Fleming MedalRecipients |publisher=AGU |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*2015 - [[National Academy of Sciences]], Arctowski Medal<ref name=\"Arctowski Medal\">{{cite web |title=Arctowski Medal Recipients |url=http://www.nasonline.org/programs/awards/arctowski-medal.html |website=NAS Arctowski Medals |publisher=National Academy of Sciences |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books authored===\nPhysics of the Jovian Magnetosphere<ref name=\"Jovian Magnetosphere Book\">{{cite book |last1=Dessler |first1=A. J. |title=Physics of the Jovian Magnetosphere |date=October 2009 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780511564574 |url=https://doi.org/10.1017/CBO9780511564574 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Selected articles===\n\nDessler, A. J., Early History of Rice University Space Science Department.<ref name=\"Space Dept. Hist.\">{{cite web |last1=Dessler |first1=Alexander |title=Early History of Rice University Space Science Department |url=http://space.rice.edu/alumni/pdf/rice_space_science_history.pdf |website=Early History of Rice University Space Science Department |publisher=Rice Space Institute |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDessler, A. J. and E. N. Parker, Hydromagnetic theory of geomagnetic storms.<ref name=\"Hydromagnetic Theory of Geomagnetic Storms\">{{cite journal |last1=Dessler |first1=A. J. |last2=Parker |first2=E. N. |title=Hydromagnetic theory of geomagnetic storms |journal=Journal of Geophysical research |date=December 1959 |volume=64 |issue=12 |page=2239-2252 |doi=10.1029/JZ064i012p02239 |url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/JZ064i012p02239 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDessler, A. J., Solar wind and [[interplanetary magnetic field]].<ref name=\"Solar Wind article\" />\n\nHill, T. W. and A. J. Dessler, Plasma motions in planetary magnetospheres.<ref name=\"Plasma Planetary Magnetospheres\">{{cite journal |last1=Hill |first1=T. W. |last2=Dessler |first2=A. J. |title=Plasma Motions in Planetary Magnetospheres |journal=Science |date=19 April 1991 |volume=252 |issue=5004 |page=410-415 |doi=10.1126/science.252.5004.410 |url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/252/5004/410 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHill, T. W., A. J. Dessler, and F. C. Michel, Configuration of the Jovian magnetosphere.<ref name=\"Jovian Magnetosphere\">{{cite journal |last1=Hill |first1=T. W. |last2=Desler |first2=A. J. |last3=Michel |first3=F. C. |title=Configuration of the Jovian magnetosphere |journal=Geophysical Research Letters |date=May 1974 |volume=1 |issue=1 |page=3-6 |doi=10.1029/GL001i001p00003 |url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/GL001i001p00003}}</ref>\n\nDessler, A. J., The Role of Space Science in Graduate Education.<ref name=\"Space Science for Graduate Students\">{{cite journal |last1=Desler |first1=A. J. |title=The role of space science in graduate education |journal=Eos, Transactions American Geophysical Union |date=September 1968 |volume=49 |issue=3 |page=549-554 |doi=10.1029/TR049i003p00549 |url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1029/TR049i003p00549 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDessler, A. J., The Role of Basic Research in Universities.<ref name=\"Role of Basic Research\">{{cite journal |last1=Dessler |first1=A. J. |title=The role of basic research in universities |journal=Eos, Transactions American Geophysical Union |date=September 1969 |volume=50 |issue=9 |page=508-511 |doi=10.1029/EO050i009p00508 |url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/EO050i009p00508 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dessler, Alexander J.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rice University faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rice University faculty]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scientists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Dallas faculty]]\n[[Category:California Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona staff]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Geophysical Union]]\n[[Category:Lockheed Missiles and Space Company people]]\n[[Category:American astrophysicists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American astrophysicist (b. 1928)}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Alexander J. Dessler\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1928|10|21}}\n| birth_place       = [[San Francisco, California]] United States\n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       =  USA\n| fields            = [[Magnetospheric Physics]], [[Heliophysics]], Jovian Physics\n| workplaces        = [[Lockheed Missiles and Space Company]], <br/>[[Rice University]],<br/>[[Lunar and Planetary Laboratory]], [[University of Arizona]] <br/>[[Texas A & M University]]\n| alma_mater        = [[California Institute of Technology]],<br/>[[Duke University]]\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = 1956\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[William M. Fairbank]]\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = Arthur A. Few; Thomas W. Hill; David Cummings, David Criswell, William Sorenson, Milo Schield, Henry B. Garrett, Steve Bowling, Yong Yang, Jie Zhan\n| notable_students  = Arthur A. Few; Thomas W. Hill; David Cummings; Henry B. Garrett\n| known_for         = Earth's Magnetosphere; Jupiter's Magnetosphere; Founding Chairman of the Department of Space Science, [[Rice University]].\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = Macelwane Medal; Fleming Medal, [[Arctowski Medal]]\n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = Lorraine Barbara Dessler\n| module      = \n}}\n\n'''Alexander J. Dessler''',  born October 21, 1928, in San Francisco, California, is a [[space scientist]] known for conceiving the term [[heliosphere]].<ref name=\"TAMU Adj.Page\">{{cite web |last1=Dessler |first1=Alexander J. |title=Biographical Sketch |url=https://atmo.tamu.edu/people/profiles/adjunct-faculty/dessleralex.html |website=AJD, CV |publisher=Texas A&M University Atmospheric Sciences |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Solar Wind article\">{{cite journal |last1=Dessler |first1=A. J. |title=Solar wind and interplanetary magnetic field |journal=Reviews of Geophysics |date=February 1967 |volume=5 |issue=1 |page=1-41 |doi=10.1029/RG005i001p00001 |url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/RG005i001p00001 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and Education==\nDessler received a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] in [[Physics]] from the [[California Institute of Technology]] in 1952 and a [[Ph.D]] in Physics from [[Duke University]] in 1956.<ref name=\"TAMU Adj.Page\" /><ref name=\"Duke Alumni\">{{cite web |title=Dept. of Physics Alumni |url=https://phy.duke.edu/alumni/alexander-j-dessler |website=Dept. of Physics Alumni |publisher=Duke University Trinity College of Arts and Sciences |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDessler began his career at [[Lockheed Missiles and Space Company]]. In 1963, while at the [[Southwest Center for Advanced Studies]], now [[University of Texas at Dallas]], he was recruited by Rice University president [[Kenneth S. Pitzer]] to found the world's first university \"Space Science\" department, as a response to [[John F. Kennedy|President John F. Kennedy's]] [[Address at Rice University on the Nation's Space Effort|Moon Speech]], delivered at Rice on September 12, 1962.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dick |first1=Steven J. |last2=Launius |first2=Roger D. |title=Societal Impact of Spaceflight |date=2007 |publisher=National aeronautics and Space administration Office of External Relations History Division |location=Washington D.C. |isbn=978-0-16-080190-7 |page=456..458 |url=https://history.nasa.gov/sp4801-chapter23.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Reiff |first1=Patricia |title=About Space Science at Rice University |url=http://space.rice.edu/alumni/about.html |website=About Space Science at Rice University |publisher=Rice Space Institute |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe is [[emeritus professor]] of [[Space physics|Space Physics]] and [[Astronomy]] at Rice University, active from 1963 to 1992. His research subject areas are [[magnetospheric physics]], planetary magnetospheres, primarily of [[magnetosphere of Jupiter|Jupiter]] and [[planetary science]].  He was founding chair of the Department of Space Science at Rice University, later known as the Department of Space Physics and Astronomy.<ref name=\"NYT Alfven\">{{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=Walter |title=Hannes Alfven, 86, Founder Of Field in Physics, Is Dead |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/05/obituaries/hannes-alfven-86-founder-of-field-in-physics-is-dead.html?searchResultPosition=2 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |issue=Section B Pg. 22 |publisher=New York Times |date=5 April 1995}}</ref>\nDessler served three terms as chair of the department and retired in 1992.<ref name=\"Space Science Bldg. 1965\">{{cite web |title=Space Science Building, 1965 |url=https://ricehistorycorner.com/2011/09/29/space-science-building-1965/ |website=Rice History Corner |publisher=Rice University}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Dick |first1=Steven J. |last2=Launius |first2=Roger D. |title=Societal Impact of Spaceflight |date=2007 |publisher=National aeronautics and Space administration Office of External Relations History Division |location=Washington D.C. |isbn=978-0-16-080190-7 |page=456..458 |url=https://history.nasa.gov/sp4801-chapter23.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Dessler became Senior Research Scientist at the Lunar and Planetary Laboratory, [[University of Arizona]], until 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boyd |first1=Jade |title=Rice space physics pioneer recognized by National Academy |url=https://news.rice.edu/2015/01/26/rice-space-physics-pioneer-recognized-by-national-academy/ |website=Rice News and Media |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> He is retired and an adjunct professor of Space Physics at Texas A & M University.<ref>{{cite web |title=Adjunct and Emeritus Faculty |url=https://atmo.tamu.edu/people/profiles/adjunct-faculty/dessleralex.html |website=Adjunct and Emeritus Faculty |publisher=Texas A&M Atmospheric Sciences |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Space Science Bldg. 1965\" />  \n\nAt the ''Possible Relationships Between Solar Activity and Meteorological Phenomena'' symposium, [[Goddard Space Flight Center]], November 7-8, 1973, [[Charles Greely Abbot|Charles Greely Abbot's]] lifelong work on solar activity provided the foundation for research as a possible driver for Earth [[weather]]. In addressing the topic, A. J. Dessler commented that any increased energy received in Earth's [[troposphere]] due to increased solar activity is negligible, and that correlations alone do not establish causation. The challenges facing scientists with complex systems like the planet's weather require finding a coupling mechanism. He suggested to continue seeking physical mechanisms.<ref name=\"Solar Activity and Earth Weather\">{{cite web |last1=Bendeen |first1=William R. |last2=Maran |first2=Stephen P. |title=POSSIBLE RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN SOLAR ACTIVITY AND METEOROLOGICAL PHENOMENA |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19760007440.pdf |website=NRTS NASA |publisher=NASA Goddard Space Flight Center |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Dressler refuted the proposition put forth by retired [[NASA]] scientist [[Addison Bain]] concerning the causes and combustion of the [[Hindenburg disaster]]. Dessler described Bain's incendiary paint theory as flawed science based on the [[stoichiometry]] of the coating's composition, the very slow burn rate of the metallic coating of the airship, and the lack of a high enough energy source to ignite the coating.<ref name=\"Hindenburg Paint Refutation\">{{cite web |last1=Dessler |first1=A. J. |title=The Hindenburg hydrogen fire: Fatal flaws in the Addison Bain incendiary paint theory |url=http://spot.colorado.edu/%E2%88%BCdziadeck/zf/LZ129fire.pdf |publisher=University of Colorado at Boulder |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ChemMatters Hindenburg Article\">{{cite web |last1=Graham |first1=Tim |title=Hindenburg: Formula for Disaster |url=chemmatters-dec2007-hindenburg (5).pdf |website=CemMatters |publisher=acs.org |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDessler and his wife Lorraine had four children, including Texas A & M atmospheric scientist [[Andrew Dessler]].\n\n==Awards and honors==\n*1963 - [[American Geophysical Union]] [[James B. Macelwane Medal|Macelwane Medal]].<ref name=Macelwane> {{cite web|title=AJ Dessler Macelwane |url=https://www.agu.org/Honor-and-Recognize/Honors/Union-Medals/James-B-Macelwane-Medal|publisher=[[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU)}}</ref>  This also was the occasion of being named Fellow of the American Geophysical Union<ref name=\"AGU Fellow\">{{cite web |title=Honors Fellows |url=https://honors.agu.org/honorsfellow/1599-dessler/ |website=AGU Fellows |publisher=AGU |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*1993 - American Geophysical Union, John Adam Fleming Medal Winner<ref name=\"John Adam Fleming Medal\">{{cite web |title=John Adam Fleming Medal |url=https://www.agu.org/Honor-and-Recognize/Honors/Union-Medals/John-Adam-Fleming-Medal |website=AGU John Adam Fleming MedalRecipients |publisher=AGU |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*2015 - [[National Academy of Sciences]], Arctowski Medal<ref name=\"Arctowski Medal\">{{cite web |title=Arctowski Medal Recipients |url=http://www.nasonline.org/programs/awards/arctowski-medal.html |website=NAS Arctowski Medals |publisher=National Academy of Sciences |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books authored===\nPhysics of the Jovian Magnetosphere<ref name=\"Jovian Magnetosphere Book\">{{cite book |last1=Dessler |first1=A. J. |title=Physics of the Jovian Magnetosphere |date=October 2009 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780511564574 |url=https://doi.org/10.1017/CBO9780511564574 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Selected articles===\n\nDessler, A. J., Early History of Rice University Space Science Department.<ref name=\"Space Dept. Hist.\">{{cite web |last1=Dessler |first1=Alexander |title=Early History of Rice University Space Science Department |url=http://space.rice.edu/alumni/pdf/rice_space_science_history.pdf |website=Early History of Rice University Space Science Department |publisher=Rice Space Institute |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDessler, A. J. and E. N. Parker, Hydromagnetic theory of geomagnetic storms.<ref name=\"Hydromagnetic Theory of Geomagnetic Storms\">{{cite journal |last1=Dessler |first1=A. J. |last2=Parker |first2=E. N. |title=Hydromagnetic theory of geomagnetic storms |journal=Journal of Geophysical research |date=December 1959 |volume=64 |issue=12 |page=2239-2252 |doi=10.1029/JZ064i012p02239 |url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/JZ064i012p02239 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDessler, A. J., Solar wind and [[interplanetary magnetic field]].<ref name=\"Solar Wind article\" />\n\nHill, T. W. and A. J. Dessler, Plasma motions in planetary magnetospheres.<ref name=\"Plasma Planetary Magnetospheres\">{{cite journal |last1=Hill |first1=T. W. |last2=Dessler |first2=A. J. |title=Plasma Motions in Planetary Magnetospheres |journal=Science |date=19 April 1991 |volume=252 |issue=5004 |page=410-415 |doi=10.1126/science.252.5004.410 |url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/252/5004/410 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHill, T. W., A. J. Dessler, and F. C. Michel, Configuration of the Jovian magnetosphere.<ref name=\"Jovian Magnetosphere\">{{cite journal |last1=Hill |first1=T. W. |last2=Desler |first2=A. J. |last3=Michel |first3=F. C. |title=Configuration of the Jovian magnetosphere |journal=Geophysical Research Letters |date=May 1974 |volume=1 |issue=1 |page=3-6 |doi=10.1029/GL001i001p00003 |url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/GL001i001p00003}}</ref>\n\nDessler, A. J., The Role of Space Science in Graduate Education.<ref name=\"Space Science for Graduate Students\">{{cite journal |last1=Desler |first1=A. J. |title=The role of space science in graduate education |journal=Eos, Transactions American Geophysical Union |date=September 1968 |volume=49 |issue=3 |page=549-554 |doi=10.1029/TR049i003p00549 |url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1029/TR049i003p00549 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDessler, A. J., The Role of Basic Research in Universities.<ref name=\"Role of Basic Research\">{{cite journal |last1=Dessler |first1=A. J. |title=The role of basic research in universities |journal=Eos, Transactions American Geophysical Union |date=September 1969 |volume=50 |issue=9 |page=508-511 |doi=10.1029/EO050i009p00508 |url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/EO050i009p00508 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dessler, Alexander J.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rice University faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rice University faculty]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scientists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Dallas faculty]]\n[[Category:California Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona staff]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Geophysical Union]]\n[[Category:Lockheed Missiles and Space Company people]]\n[[Category:American astrophysicists]]\n", "name_user": "Carlton Colmenares", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed had to have four children.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_J._Dessler"}
{"title_page": "Banda Islands", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox islands\n|name = Banda Islands\n|image_name = BandaBesarIslandSeenFromFortBelgica.JPG\n|image_caption = Banda Besar island seen from [[Fort Belgica]]\n|native_name = \n|native_name_link =\n|location = [[Oceania]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|4|35|S|129|55|E|region:ID_type:isle|display=title,inline}}\n|archipelago = [[Maluku Islands]]\n|total_islands = \n|major_islands = \n|area_km2 = 172\n|highest_mount = \n|elevation_m = \n|country = Indonesia\n|country_admin_divisions_title = \n|country_admin_divisions = \n|country_largest_city = \n|country_largest_city_area = \n|population = 18,934\n|population_as_of = 2015\n|density_km2 = 110\n|ethnic_groups =\n}}\n\n[[File:Maluku Islands en.png|right|250px|thumb|Location of the Banda Islands in the center of the [[Maluku Islands]]]]\n[[File:Banda Islands en.png|thumb|250px|Map of the Banda Islands]]\n\nThe '''Banda Islands''' ({{lang-id|Kepulauan Banda}}) are a [[volcanic group]] of ten small [[volcanic island]]s in the [[Banda Sea]], about {{convert|140|km|0|abbr=on}} south of [[Seram Island]] and about {{convert|2000|km|0|abbr=on}} east of [[Java (island)|Java]], and constitute an administrative district (''kecamatan'') within the [[Central Maluku Regency]] in the [[Indonesia]]n province of [[Maluku (Indonesian province)|Maluku]]. The main town and administrative centre is [[Bandanaira]], located on the island of the same name. They rise out of {{convert|4|to|6|km|adj=on}} deep ocean and have a total land area of approximately {{convert|172|km2}}. They had a population of 18,934 at the 2015 Census.<ref>Biro Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2011.</ref> Until the mid-19th century the Banda Islands were the world's only source of the spices [[nutmeg]] and [[mace (spice)|mace]], produced from the nutmeg tree. The islands are also popular destinations for [[scuba diving]] and [[snorkeling]].\n\n== History ==\n\n===Pre-European history===\nThe first documented human presence in the Banda Islands comes from a rockshelter site on Pulau Ay that was in use at least 8,000 years ago.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lape|first1=Peter|title=Die erste Besiedlung auf den Banda-Inseln: 8000 Jahre Arch\u00e4ologie auf den Molukken (The first settlement in the Banda Islands: 8000 years of archeology in the Moluccas)|journal=Antike Welt|date=2013|volume=5|issue=13|pages=9\u201313}}</ref>\n\nThe earliest mention of the Banda Islands are found in Chinese records dating as far back as 200 BCE though there's speculation that it's mentioned in earlier Indian sources. The Srivijaya kingdom had extensive trade contacts with the Banda Islands. Also during this period (from the late 13th century and onwards) Islam arrived in the region. It soon became established in the area.<ref>{{Cite book|title=International Dictionary of Historic Places, Volume 5: Asia and Oceania|last=|first=|publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn Publishers|year=1996|isbn=1-884964-04-4|editor-last=Schellinger|editor-first=Paul|location=Chicago|pages=87|editor-last2=Salkin|editor-first2=Robert}}</ref>\n\nBefore the arrival of Europeans, Banda had an [[oligarchic]] form of government led by ''orang kaya'' ('rich men') and the Bandanese had an active and independent role in trade throughout the archipelago.<ref name=\"RICKLEFSp24\">{{cite book| last =Ricklefs  | first =M.C.| title =A History of Modern Indonesia Since c.1300, 2nd Edition  | publisher =MacMillan  | year =1991  | location =London  | page =24 | isbn = 978-0-333-57689-2 }}</ref> Banda was the world's only source of [[nutmeg]] and [[mace (spice)|mace]], spices used as flavourings, medicines, and preserving agents that were at the time highly valued in European markets. They were sold by [[Arab]] traders to the [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]]s for exorbitant prices. The traders did not divulge the exact location of their source and no European was able to deduce their location.\n\nThe first written accounts of Banda are in ''Suma Oriental'', a book written by the [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] [[apothecary]] [[Tom\u00e9 Pires]] who was based in [[Malacca]] from 1512 to 1515 but visited Banda several times. On his first visit, he interviewed the Portuguese and the far more knowledgeable Malay sailors in Malacca. He estimated the early sixteenth century population to be 2500\u20133000. He reported the Bandanese as being part of an Indonesia-wide trading network and the only native Malukan long-range traders taking cargo to Malacca, although shipments from Banda were also being made by [[Javanese people|Javanese]] traders.\n\nIn addition to the production of nutmeg and mace, Banda maintained significant [[entrep\u00f4t]] trade; goods that moved through Banda included cloves from [[Ternate]] and [[Tidore]] in the north, [[bird-of-paradise]] feathers from the [[Aru Islands Regency|Aru Islands]] and [[Western New Guinea]], ''massoi'' bark for traditional medicines and salves. In exchange, Banda predominantly received rice and cloth; namely light cotton ''[[batik]]'' from [[Java]], ''[[Calico (textile)|calicoes]]'' from [[India]] and ''[[ikat]]'' from the [[Lesser Sundas]].  In 1603, an average quality ''[[sarong]]''-sized cloth traded for eighteen kilograms of nutmeg.  Some of these textiles were then on-sold, ending up in [[Halmahera]] and [[New Guinea]].  Coarser ''ikat'' from the Lesser Sundas was traded for [[sago]] from the [[Kei Islands]], [[Aru Islands Regency|Aru]] and [[Seram]].\n\n===Portuguese===\nIn August 1511 on behalf of the king of [[Portugal]], [[Afonso de Albuquerque]] conquered [[Malacca]], which at the time was the hub of Asian trade. In November of that year, after having secured Malacca and learning of the Bandas' location, Albuquerque sent an expedition of three ships led by his good friend [[Ant\u00f3nio de Abreu]] to find them. [[Malay (ethnic group)|Malay]] pilots, either recruited or forcibly conscripted, guided them via [[Java]], the [[Lesser Sundas]] and [[Ambon Island|Ambon]] to Banda, arriving in early 1512.<ref>Hannard (1991), page 7; {{cite book  | last =Milton  | first =Giles  | authorlink =Giles Milton    | title =Nathaniel's Nutmeg  | publisher =Sceptre  | year =1999  | location =London  | pages =5 and 7  | isbn = 978-0-340-69676-7 }}</ref> The first Europeans to reach the Bandas, the expedition remained in Banda for about one month, purchasing and filling their ships with Banda's nutmeg and mace, and with [[clove]]s in which Banda had a thriving entrep\u00f4t trade.<ref name=\"HANNARDp7\">Hannard (1991), page 7</ref> D'Abreu sailed through [[Ambon Island|Ambon]] and [[Seram Island|Seram]] while his second in command [[Francisco Serr\u00e3o]] went ahead towards the Maluku islands, was shipwrecked and ended up in [[Ternate]].<ref name=\"RICKLEFSp25\"/> Distracted by hostilities elsewhere in the archipelago, such as Ambon and Ternate, the Portuguese did not return until 1529; a Portuguese trader Captain Garcia Henriques landed troops in the Bandas. Five of the Banda islands were within gunshot of each other and he realised that a fort on the main island Neira would give him full control of the group. The Bandanese were, however, hostile to such a plan, and their warlike antics were both costly and tiresome to Garcia whose men were attacked when they attempted to build a fort. From then on, the Portuguese were infrequent visitors to the islands preferring to buy their nutmeg from traders in Malacca.<ref>{{cite book  | last =Milton  | first =Giles  | authorlink =Giles Milton    | title =Nathaniel's Nutmeg  | publisher =Sceptre  | year =1999  | location =London  | pages =5 and 7  | isbn = 978-0-340-69676-7 }}</ref>\n\nUnlike other eastern Indonesian islands, such as [[Ambon Island|Ambon]], [[Solor]], [[Ternate]] and [[Morotai]], the Bandanese displayed no enthusiasm for Christianity or the Europeans who brought it in the sixteenth century, and no serious attempt was made to Christianise the Bandanese.<ref name=\"RICKLEFSp25\">{{cite book  | last =Ricklefs  | first =M.C. | title =A History of Modern Indonesia Since c.1300, 2nd Edition  | publisher =MacMillan  | year =1993  | location =London  | page =25 | isbn = 978-0-333-57689-2 }}</ref> Maintaining their independence, the Bandanese never allowed the Portuguese to build a fort or a permanent post in the islands. Ironically though, it was this lack of ports which brought the Dutch to trade at Banda instead of the clove islands of Ternate and Tidore.\n\n===Dutch Control===\n{{main|Governorate of the Banda Islands}}\n[[File:Fort Nassau 1646.jpg|right|thumb|[[Fort Nassau, Banda Islands|Fort Nassau]] in 1646]]\n\nThe Dutch followed the Portuguese to Banda but were to have a much more dominating and lasting presence. Dutch-Bandanese relations were mutually resentful from the outset, with Holland's first merchants complaining of Bandanese reneging on agreed deliveries and price, and cheating on quantity and quality. For the Bandanese, on the other hand, although they welcomed another competitor purchaser for their spices, the items of trade offered by the Dutch\u2014heavy woolens, and damasks, unwanted manufactured goods, for example\u2014were usually unsuitable in comparison to traditional trade products. The [[Javanese people|Javanese]], [[Arab]] and [[India]]n, and Portuguese traders for example brought indispensable items along with steel knives, copper, medicines and prized [[China|Chinese]] [[porcelain]].{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nAs much as the Dutch disliked dealing with the Bandanese, the trade was a highly profitable one with spices selling for 300 times the purchase price in Banda. This amply justified the expense and risk in shipping them to Europe. The allure of such profits saw an increasing number of Dutch expeditions; it was soon seen that in trade with the East Indies, competition from each would eat into all their profits. Thus the competitors united to form the ''Vereenigde Oostindische Compagnie (VOC)'' (the \u2018[[Dutch East Indies Company]]) in 1602.<ref name = \"uclwxl\">Hannard (1991)</ref>\n\nUntil the early seventeenth century the Bandas were ruled by a group of leading citizens, the ''orang kaya'' (literally 'rich men'); each of these was head of a district. At the time nutmeg was one of the \"fine spices\" kept expensive in Europe by disciplined manipulation of the market, but a desirable commodity for Dutch traders in the ports of India as well; economic historian [[Fernand Braudel]] notes that India consumed twice as much as Europe.<ref>Braudel 1984, p. 219</ref> A number of Banda's ''orang kaya'' were persuaded by the Dutch to sign a treaty granting the Dutch a monopoly on spice purchases. Even though the Bandanese had little understanding of the significance of the treaty known as 'The Eternal Compact', or that not all Bandanese leaders had signed, it would later be used to justify Dutch troops being brought in to defend their monopoly.\n\nIn April 1609, Admiral [[Pieter Willemsz. Verhoeff]] arrived at Banda Neira with a request by [[Maurice, Prince of Orange]] to build a fort on the island (the eventual [[Fort Nassau, Banda Islands|Fort Nassau]]). The Bandanese were not excited about this idea. On 22 May, before building of the fort had started, the ''orang kaya'' called a meeting with the Dutch admiral, purportedly to negotiate prices. Instead, they led Verhoeff and two high-ranked men into an ambush and decapitated them and subsequently killed 46 of the Dutch visitors. [[Jan Pietersz Coen]], who was a lower-ranked merchant on the expedition, managed to escape, but the traumatic event likely influenced his future attitude towards the Bandanese.<ref>Opstall, M.E. van, ''De reis van de vloot van Pieter Willemsz Verhoeff naar Azi\u00eb 1607\u20131612'', Utrecht University, 1972, pp. 95\u201398.</ref>\n\n[[File:Fort Belgica 1824.jpg|thumb|Fort Belgica in 1824]]\n\n===English-Dutch rivalry===\nWhile Portuguese and Spanish activity in the region had weakened, the English had built fortified trading posts on tiny Ai and [[Run (island)|Run]] islands, ten to twenty kilometres from the main Banda Islands. With the English paying higher prices, they were significantly undermining Dutch aims for a monopoly. As Anglo-Dutch tensions increased in 1611 the Dutch built the larger and more strategic [[Fort Belgica]] above Fort Nassau.\n\nIn 1615, the Dutch invaded Ai with 900 men whereupon the English retreated to Run where they regrouped. Japanese mercenaries served in the Dutch forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wardsan.travellerspoint.com/s21/|title=Asia 2008\u201309|work=travellerspoint.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.library.utoronto.ca/details?7626150|title=Merchant kings : when companies ruled the world, 1600\u20131900 / \u2013 University of Toronto Libraries|work=utoronto.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danbyrnes.com.au/lostworlds/timeline/lwstory7.htm|title=Lost Worlds Page 7 \u2013 From 1600\u20131700|first=Dan|last=Byrnes|work=danbyrnes.com.au}}</ref> That same night, the English launched a surprise counter-attack on Ai, retaking the island and killing 200 Dutchmen. A year later, a much stronger Dutch force attacked Ai. This time the defenders were able to hold off the attack with cannon fire, but after a month of siege they ran out of ammunition. The Dutch slaughtered the defenders, and afterwards strengthened the fort, renaming it 'Fort Revenge'.\n\n[[File:COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Militairen bij het standbeeld van Koning Willem III op Banda TMnr 10018594.jpg|thumb|upright|Colonial soldiers standing guard next to the statue of [[King Willem III of the Netherlands]], representing [[Dutch empire|Dutch dominance]] on Banda.]]\n\n===Massacre of the Bandanese===\n{{main|Dutch conquest of the Banda Islands}}\nNewly appointed VOC governor-general [[Jan Pieterszoon Coen]] set about enforcing Dutch monopoly over the Banda's spice trade. In 1621 well-armed soldiers were landed on Bandaneira Island and within a few days they had also occupied neighbouring and larger [[Lontar island|Lontar]]. The ''orang kaya'' were forced at gunpoint to sign an unfeasibly arduous treaty, one that was in fact impossible to keep, thus providing Coen an excuse to use superior Dutch force against the Bandanese.<ref name = \"uclwxl\"/> The Dutch quickly noted a number of alleged violations of the new treaty, in response to which Coen launched a punitive massacre. Japanese mercenaries were hired to deal with the ''orang kaya'',<ref>{{cite news |title=The world's oldest clove tree  |author=Simon Worrall |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-18551857 |newspaper=BBC News |date=23 June 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/fooc/2012/07/120706_fooc_oldest_clove_tree.shtml \u8bb0\u8005\u6765\u9e3f\uff1a\u0093\u963f\u548c\u0094\u7684\u4f20\u5947] BBC China</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.matatraders.com/fair-trade-movement/2011/12/reigniting-the-mystique-of-the-%E2%80%98spice-islands%E2%80%99-to-benefit-farmers/|title=Reigniting the Mystique of the 'Spice Islands' to Benefit Farmers|date=16 December 2011|work=matatraders.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://herbicidefree.co/2014/01/18/nothing-changes/|title=Nothing changes|date=18 January 2014|work=herbicidefree.co}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lloydthomas.org/1-IsraelTimeLine/6-1543-1929/1543-1820.htm|title=1542\u20131820 AD/CE|work=lloydthomas.org}}</ref> forty of whom were beheaded with their heads impaled and displayed on bamboo spears.<ref name=\"Unoki2012\">{{cite book|author=Ko Unoki|title=Mergers, Acquisitions and Global Empires: Tolerance, Diversity and the Success of M&A|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6UaeL64p-ukC&pg=PA56|date=12 October 2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-21538-4|page=56}}</ref> The butchering and beheadings were carried out by the Japanese for the Dutch.<ref name=\"Krondl2008\">{{cite book|author=Michael Krondl|title=The Taste of Conquest: The Rise and Fall of the Three Great Cities of Spice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ewNtDrKa5yYC&pg=PT209|date=28 October 2008|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-345-50982-6|page=209}}</ref>\n\nThe islanders were also tortured by the Dutch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2012/11/26/165657050/no-innocent-spice-the-secret-story-of-nutmeg-life-and-death|title=No Innocent Spice: The Secret Story of Nutmeg, Life And Death|work=npr.org}}</ref> The Bandanese chiefs were tortured by the Dutch and Japanese.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nicholas.duke.edu/nature-rambles/frigates-war-canoes-and-volcanoes/|title=Frigates, War Canoes, and Volcanoes|date=26 October 2015|work=duke.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:xTHp2w0IAYwJ:blogs.nicholas.duke.edu/nature-rambles/frigates-war-canoes-and-volcanoes/%20&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us |title=Frigates, War Canoes, and Volcanoes |date=26 October 2015 |work=googleusercontent.com }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nicholas.duke.edu/nature-rambles/environmental-health/feed/|title=environmental health \u2013 Nature Rambles|work=duke.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:1FdHoxLNRnUJ:blogs.nicholas.duke.edu/nature-rambles/environmental-health/feed/%20&cd=2&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us |title=environmental health \u2013 Nature Rambles|work=googleusercontent.com }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"Turner2008\">{{cite book|author=Jack Turner|title=Spice: The History of a Temptation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EzXF7cpeMr0C&pg=PA291|date=10 December 2008|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-49122-0|pages=290\u2013291}}</ref>\n\nThe Dutch carved 68 parcels out of the islands after the enslavement and slaughter of the natives.<ref name=\"PrakWebb2005\">{{cite book|author1=Maarten Prak|author2=Diane Webb|title=The Dutch Republic in the Seventeenth Century: The Golden Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JhIxrykbrKUC&pg=PA119|date=22 September 2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-84352-2|page=119}}</ref><ref name=\"Milton2012\">{{cite book|author=Giles Milton|title=Nathaniel's Nutmeg|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nQ1AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT163|date=12 April 2012|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|isbn=978-1-4447-1771-6|page=163}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/29386.Nathaniel_s_Nutmeg|title=Nathaniel's Nutmeg|work=goodreads.com}}</ref>\n\nThe population of the Banda Islands prior to Dutch conquest is generally estimated to have been around 13,000\u201315,000 people, some of whom were Malay and Javanese traders, as well as Chinese and Arabs. The actual numbers of Bandanese who were killed, forcibly expelled or fled the islands in 1621 remain uncertain. But readings of historical sources suggest around one thousand Bandanese likely survived in the islands, and were spread throughout the nutmeg groves as forced labourers.<ref>Hanna 1991, p.54; Loth 1995, p.18</ref><ref name=\"Tarling1999\">{{cite book|author=Nicholas Tarling|authorlink=Nicholas Tarling|title=The Cambridge History of Southeast Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GIz4CDTCOwcC&pg=PA86|year=1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-66370-0|pages=86\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Tarling1992\">{{cite book|author=Nicholas Tarling|title=The Cambridge History of Southeast Asia: Volume 1, From Early Times to C.1800|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rOw8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA430|year=1992|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-35505-6|pages=430\u2013}}</ref> The Dutch subsequently re-settled the islands with imported slaves, convicts and indentured labourers (to work the nutmeg plantations), as well as immigrants from elsewhere in Indonesia. Most survivors fled as refugees to the islands of their trading partners, in particular [[Keffing]] and [[Guli Guli]] in the [[Seram|Seram Laut]] chain and [[Kei Islands|Kei Besar]].<ref name = \"uclwxl\"/> Shipments of surviving Bandanese were also sent to Batavia ([[Jakarta]]) to work as slaves in developing the city and its fortress. Some 530 of these individuals were later returned to the islands because of their much-needed expertise in nutmeg cultivation (something sorely lacking among newly arrived Dutch settlers).<ref>Hanna 1991, p.55; Loth 1995, p.24</ref>\n\nWhereas up until this point the Dutch presence had been simply as traders, that was sometimes treaty-based, the Banda conquest marked the start of the first overt colonial rule in Indonesia, albeit under the auspices of the VOC.\n\n===VOC Monopoly===\n[[File:Banda Neira 1724.jpg|thumb|Banda Neira in 1724]]\n\nHaving nearly eradicated the islands' native population, Coen divided the productive land of approximately half a million nutmeg trees into sixty-eight 1.2-hectare ''perken''. These land parcels were then handed to Dutch planters known as ''perkeniers'' of which 34 were on [[Lontar island|Lontar]], 31 on Ai and 3 on Neira.  With few Bandanese left to work them, slaves from elsewhere were brought in.<ref name=\"Brown2004\">{{cite book|author=Iem Brown|title=The Territories of Indonesia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lfPJAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA260|date=17 June 2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-35541-8|page=170}}</ref> Now enjoying control of the nutmeg production, the VOC paid the ''perkeniers'' 1/122nd of the Dutch market price for nutmeg; however, the ''perkeniers'' still profited immensely building substantial villas with opulent imported European decorations.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nThe outlying island of Run was harder for the VOC to control and they exterminated all nutmeg trees there. The production and export of nutmeg was a VOC monopoly for almost two hundred years. [[Fort Belgica]], one of many forts built by the [[Dutch East India Company]], is one of the largest remaining European forts in Indonesia.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\n===English-Dutch rivalry continues===\n{{further|Invasion of the Spice Islands}}\nThough not physically present at the Banda Islands, the English claimed the small island of [[Run (island)|Run]] until 1667 when, under the [[Treaty of Breda (1667)]], the Dutch and English agreed to maintain the colonial [[status quo]] and relinquish their respective claims.\n[[File:Banda1810Cole.jpg|thumb|View of the Island of Banda-Neira captured by the British on 9 August 1810]]\n\nIn 1810, the Kingdom of Holland was a vassal of Napoleonic France and hence in conflict with Britain.  The French and British were each seeking to control lucrative Indian Ocean trade routes.  On 10 May 1810, a squadron consisting of the 36-gun frigate {{HMS|Caroline}}, [[French frigate Pi\u00e9montaise (1804)|HMS ''Piedmontaise'']], formerly a French frigate, 18-gun [[Cruizer class brig-sloop|sloop]] {{HMS|Barracouta}}, and the 12-gun transport {{HMS|Mandarin|1810|6}} left [[Chennai|Madras]] with money, supplies and troops to support the garrison at [[Ambon Island|Amboyna]], recently captured from the Dutch.  The frigates and sloop carried a hundred officers and men of the [[102nd Regiment of Foot (Royal Madras Fusiliers)|Madras European Regiment]], while the ''Mandarin'' carried supplies.  The squadron was commanded by Captain [[Christopher Cole (Royal Navy officer)|Christopher Cole]], with Captain Charles Foote on the ''Piedmontaise'' and Captain Richard Kenah aboard the ''Barracouta''.  After departing from Madras, Cole informed Foote and Kenah of Cole's plan to capture the Bandas; Foote and Kenah agreed. In Singapore, Captain [[Richard Spencer (Royal Navy officer)|Spencer]] informed Cole that over 700 regular Dutch troops may be located in the Bandas.<ref name=\"Adkins\">{{cite book |last1=Adkins |first1=Roy |last2=Adkins |first2=Lesley |title=The War for All the Oceans: From Nelson at the Nile to Napoleon at Waterloo |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3u9jdSlnGiMC&pg=PA345|year=2008 |publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-0-14-311392-8 |pages=344\u2013355}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Annual biography and obituary |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h-UKAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA114|volume=21 |year=1837 |publisher=Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme, and Brown |location=London |pages=114\u2013123 |chapter=Sir Christopher Cole, K.C.B. }}</ref>\n\nThe squadron took a circuitous route to avoid alerting the Dutch.  On 9 August 1810, the British appeared at [[Banda Neira]].  They quickly stormed the island and attacked [[Fort Belgica|Belgica Castle]] at sunrise.  The battle was over within hours, with the Dutch surrendering [[Fort Nassau, Banda Islands|Fort Nassau]] \u2013 after some subterfuge \u2013 and within days the remainder of the Banda Islands. After the Dutch surrender, Captain Charles Foote (of the ''Piedmontaise'') was appointed Lieutenant-Governor of the Banda Islands. This action was a prelude to Britain's [[Invasion of Java (1811)|invasion of Java]] in 1811.<ref name=\"Adkins\" />\n\nBefore the Dutch retook control of the islands, the British removed many nutmeg trees and transplanted them to [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]] and other British colonies.  The competition largely destroyed the value of the Banda Islands to the Dutch.<ref>{{cite news |title=Banda, the nutmeg treasure islands |first=Peter |last=Milne |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/01/16/banda-nutmeg-treasure-islands.html |newspaper=Jakarta Post |location=Jakarta |date=16 January 2011 |pages=10\u201311 |accessdate=22 December 2011 |quote=But the economic importance of the Bandas was only fleeting. With the Napoleonic wars raging across Europe, the English returned to the Bandas in the early 19th century, temporarily taking over control from the Dutch. This gave the English an opportunity to uproot hundreds of valuable nutmeg seedlings and transport them to their own colonies in Ceylon and Singapore, breaking forever the Dutch monopoly and consigning the Bandas to economic decline and irrelevance.}}</ref>\n\n===Recent history===\nIn the late 1990s, violence between Christians and Muslims and between indigenous locals and [[Transmigration program|transmigrants]] spilled over from [[Maluku sectarian conflict|intercommunal conflict]] in Ambon. The disturbance and resulting deaths damaged the previously prosperous [[tourism]] industry.<ref>Witton, Patrick (2003). Indonesia. Melbourne: Lonely Planet. {{ISBN|1-74059-154-2}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThere are seven inhabited islands and several that are uninhabited.  The inhabited islands are:\n[[File:BandaVolcano.JPG|thumb|The active volcano [[Banda Api]] in the Banda Islands]]\n[[File:Banda-0039.jpg|thumb|The main island, Banda Neira (centre) viewed from the peak of Gunung Api volcano. In the background is [[Lontar Island]] (Banda Besar).]]\nMain group:\n*[[Banda Neira]], or Naira, the island with the administrative capital and a small airfield (as well as accommodation for visitors). Present on Banda Neira is Fort Belgica, one of the largest remaining Dutch forts that are still intact in Indonesia. \n*[[Banda Api]], an active volcano (Gunung Api) with a peak of about 650 m\n*Banda Besar is the largest island (Indonesian ''besar'', big), {{convert|12|km|0|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|3|km|0|abbr=on}} wide. It has three main settlements, Lonthoir, Selamon and Waer.\n\nSome distance to the west:\n*Pulau [[Ai (island)|Ai]] or Pulau Ay\n*Pulau [[Run (island)|Run]], further west again. In the 17th century, this island was involved in an exchange between the British and the Dutch: it was exchanged for the island of Manhattan in New York.\n\nTo the east:\n*[[Pisang Island (Maluku)|Pulau Pisang]] (Banana Island), also known as Syahrir.\n\nTo the southeast:\n*Pulau Hatta, formerly Rosengain or Rozengain\n\nOthers, possibly small and/or uninhabited, are:\n*Nailaka, a short distance northeast of Pulau [[Run (island)|Run]]\n*Batu Kapal\n*Manuk, an active volcano\n*Pulau Keraka or Pulau Karaka (Crab Island)\n*Manukang\n*Hatta Reef\n\nThe islands are part of the [[Banda Sea Islands moist deciduous forests]] [[ecoregion]].\n\n==Bandanese culture==\nMost of the present-day inhabitants of the Banda Islands are descended from migrants and plantation labourers from various parts of Indonesia, as well as from indigenous Bandanese. They have inherited aspects of pre-colonial ritual practices in the Bandas that are highly valued and still performed, giving them a distinct and very local cultural identity.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lape|first1=Peter V.|title=Political dynamics and religious change in the late pre-colonial Banda Islands, Eastern Indonesia|journal=World Archaeology|date=2000|volume=32|issue=1|pages=138\u2013155|doi=10.1080/004382400409934|citeseerx=10.1.1.500.4009}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Bandanese speak a distinct dialect of [[Malay language]] which has several features distinguishing it from [[Ambonese Malay]], the better-known and more widespread dialect that forms a lingua franca in central and southeast Maluku. Bandanese Malay is famous in the region for its unique, lilting accent, but it also has a number of locally identifying words in its lexicon, many of them borrowings or [[loanwords]] from [[Dutch language|Dutch]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Winn|first1=Phillip|title=Slavery and cultural creativity in the Banda Islands|journal=Journal of Southeast Asian Studies|date=2010|volume=41|issue=3|pages=365\u2013389|doi=10.1017/s0022463410000238}}</ref>\n\nExamples :\n* fork\t: forok (Dutch vork)\n* ant\t: mir (Dutch mier)\n* spoon\t: lepe (Dutch lepel)\n* difficult : lastek (Dutch lastig)\n* floor : plur (Dutch vloer)\n* porch: stup (Dutch stoep)\n\nBanda Malay shares many [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] loanwords with Ambonese Malay not appearing in the national language, [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]. But it has comparatively fewer, and they differ in pronunciation.\n\nExamples :\n* turtle : tetaruga (Banda Malay); totoruga (Ambonese Malay) (from Portuguese tartaruga)\n* throat : gargontong (Banda Malay); gargangtang (Ambonese Malay) (from Portuguese garganta)\n\nFinally, and most noticeably, Banda Malay uses some distinct pronouns. The most immediately distinguishing is that of the second person singular familiar form of address: pan\u00e9.\n\nThe descendants of some of the Bandanese who fled Dutch conquest in the seventeenth century live in the [[Kai Islands]] (Kepulauan Kei) to the east of the Banda group, where a version of the original [[Banda language (Indonesia)|Banda language]] is still spoken in the villages of Banda Eli and Banda Elat on Kai Besar Island. While long integrated into Kei Island society, residents of these settlements continue to value the historical origins of their ancestors.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Indonesia}}\n*[[1938 Banda Sea earthquake]]\n*[[Dutch East India Company in Indonesia]]\n*[[History of Indonesia]]\n*[[List of earthquakes in Indonesia]]\n*[[List of volcanoes in Indonesia#Banda Sea]]\n*[[Maluku Islands]]\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Giles Milton]]. ''[[Nathaniel's Nutmeg]]: How One Man's Courage Changed the Course of History'' (Sceptre books, Hodder and Stoughton, London)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*Braudel, Fernand. 1984. The Perspective of the World. In: ''Civilization and Capitalism'', vol. III.\n*{{cite book  | last =  Hanna| first =Willard A.| title =Indonesian Banda: Colonialism and its Aftermath in the Nutmeg Islands| publisher =Yayasan Warisan dan Budaya Banda Naira  | year =1991| location =[[Bandanaira]] }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Lape | first1 = Peter | year = 2000 | title = Political dynamics and religious change in the late pre-colonial Banda Islands, Eastern Indonesia | journal = World Archaeology | volume = 32 | issue = 1| pages = 138\u2013155 | doi=10.1080/004382400409934| citeseerx = 10.1.1.500.4009 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Loth | first1 = Vincent C | year = 1995 | title = Pioneers and perkerniers:the Banda Islands in the seventeenth century | journal = Cakalele | volume = 6 | pages = 13\u201335 }}\n*{{cite book  | last =  Muller| first =Karl |author2=Pickell, David (ed)| title =Maluku: Indonesian Spice Islands  | publisher =Periplus Editions  | year =1997  | location =Singapore | isbn = 978-962-593-176-0 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Villiers | first1 = John | year = 1981 | title = Trade and society in the Banda Islands in the sixteenth century | journal = Modern Asian Studies | volume = 15 | issue = 4| pages = 723\u2013750 | doi=10.1017/s0026749x0000874x}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Winn | first1 = Phillip | year = 1998 | title = Banda is the Blessed Land: sacred practice and identity in the Banda Islands, Maluku | journal = Antropologi Indonesia | volume = 57 | pages = 71\u201380 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Winn | first1 = Phillip | year = 2001 | title = Graves, groves and gardens: place and identity in central Maluku, Indonesia| journal = The Asia Pacific Journal of Anthropology | volume = 2 | issue = 1| pages = 24\u201344 | doi=10.1080/14442210110001706025}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Winn | first1 = Phillip | year = 2002 | title = Everyone searches, everyone finds: moral discourse and resource use in an Indonesian Muslim community | journal = Oceania | volume = 72 | issue = 4| pages = 275\u2013292 | doi=10.1002/j.1834-4461.2002.tb02796.x}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Banda Islands}}\n{{wikivoyage|Banda Islands}}\n*{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Banda Islands |volume=3 |short=x}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090302023256/http://www.royal-navy.org/lib/index.php?title=Capture_of_Banda_Neira Capture of Banda Neira by the British Royal Navy 1810]\n*{{WWF ecoregion|name=Banda Sea Islands moist deciduous forests|id=aa0102}}\n*[http://www.spiceislandsforts.com/the-bandas/ Forts of the Spice Islands]\n\n{{Maluku-islands}}\n{{Dutch colonies|East India}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Portuguese colonialism in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Dutch East India Company]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Maluku (province)]]\n[[Category:Volcanic groups]]\n[[Category:Banda Sea]]\n[[Category:Banda Islands| ]]\n[[Category:Central Maluku Regency]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox islands\n|name = Banda Islands\n|image_name = BandaBesarIslandSeenFromFortBelgica.JPG\n|image_caption = Banda Besar island seen from [[Fort Belgica]]\n|native_name = \n|native_name_link =\n|location = [[Oceania]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|4|35|S|129|55|E|region:ID_type:isle|display=title,inline}}\n|archipelago = [[Maluku Islands]]\n|total_islands = \n|major_islands = \n|area_km2 = 172\n|highest_mount = \n|elevation_m = \n|country = Indonesia\n|country_admin_divisions_title = \n|country_admin_divisions = \n|country_largest_city = \n|country_largest_city_area = \n|population = 18,934\n|population_as_of = 2015\n|density_km2 = 110\n|ethnic_groups =\n}}\n\n[[File:Maluku Islands en.png|right|250px|thumb|Location of the Banda Islands in the center of the [[Maluku Islands]]]]\n[[File:Banda Islands en.png|thumb|250px|Map of the Banda Islands]]\n\nThe '''Banda Islands''' ({{lang-id|Kepulauan Banda}}) are a [[volcanic group]] of ten small [[volcanic island]]s in the [[Banda Sea]], about {{convert|140|km|0|abbr=on}} south of [[Seram Island]] and about {{convert|2000|km|0|abbr=on}} east of [[Java (island)|Java]], and constitute an administrative district (''kecamatan'') within the [[Central Maluku Regency]] in the [[Indonesia]]n province of [[Maluku (Indonesian province)|Maluku]]. The main town and administrative centre is [[Bandanaira]], located on the island of the same name. They rise out of {{convert|4|to|6|km|adj=on}} deep ocean and have a total land area of approximately {{convert|172|km2}}. They had a population of 18,934 at the 2015 Census.<ref>Biro Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2011.</ref> Until the mid-19th century the Banda Islands were the world's only source of the spices [[nutmeg]] and [[mace (spice)|mace]], produced from the nutmeg tree. The islands are also popular destinations for [[scuba diving]] and [[snorkeling]].\n\n== History ==\n\n===Pre-European history===\nThe first documented human presence in the Banda Islands comes from a rockshelter site on Pulau Ay that was in use at least 8,000 years ago.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lape|first1=Peter|title=Die erste Besiedlung auf den Banda-Inseln: 8000 Jahre Arch\u00e4ologie auf den Molukken (The first settlement in the Banda Islands: 8000 years of archeology in the Moluccas)|journal=Antike Welt|date=2013|volume=5|issue=13|pages=9\u201313}}</ref>\n\nThe earliest mention of the Banda Islands are found in Chinese records dating as far back as 200 BCE though there's speculation that it's mentioned in earlier Indian sources. The Srivijaya kingdom had extensive trade contacts with the Banda Islands. Also during this period (from the late 13th century and onwards) Islam arrived in the region. It soon became established in the area.<ref>{{Cite book|title=International Dictionary of Historic Places, Volume 5: Asia and Oceania|last=|first=|publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn Publishers|year=1996|isbn=1-884964-04-4|editor-last=Schellinger|editor-first=Paul|location=Chicago|pages=87|editor-last2=Salkin|editor-first2=Robert}}</ref>\n\nBefore the arrival of Europeans, Banda had an [[oligarchic]] form of government led by ''orang kaya'' ('rich men') and the Bandanese had an active and independent role in trade throughout the archipelago.<ref name=\"RICKLEFSp24\">{{cite book| last =Ricklefs  | first =M.C.| title =A History of Modern Indonesia Since c.1300, 2nd Edition  | publisher =MacMillan  | year =1991  | location =London  | page =24 | isbn = 978-0-333-57689-2 }}</ref> Banda was the world's only source of [[nutmeg]] and [[mace (spice)|mace]], spices used as flavourings, medicines, and preserving agents that were at the time highly valued in European markets. They were sold by [[Arab]] traders to the [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]]s for exorbitant prices. The traders did not divulge the exact location of their source and no European was able to deduce their location.\n\nThe first written accounts of Banda are in ''Suma Oriental'', a book written by the [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] [[apothecary]] [[Tom\u00e9 Pires]] who was based in [[Malacca]] from 1512 to 1515 but visited Banda several times. On his first visit, he interviewed the Portuguese and the far more knowledgeable Malay sailors in Malacca. He estimated the early sixteenth century population to be 2500\u20133000. He reported the Bandanese as being part of an Indonesia-wide trading network and the only native Malukan long-range traders taking cargo to Malacca, although shipments from Banda were also being made by [[Javanese people|Javanese]] traders.\n\nIn addition to the production of nutmeg and mace, Banda maintained significant [[entrep\u00f4t]] trade; goods that moved through Banda included cloves from [[Ternate]] and [[Tidore]] in the north, [[bird-of-paradise]] feathers from the [[Aru Islands Regency|Aru Islands]] and [[Western New Guinea]], ''massoi'' bark for traditional medicines and salves. In exchange, Banda predominantly received rice and cloth; namely light cotton ''[[batik]]'' from [[Java]], ''[[Calico (textile)|calicoes]]'' from [[India]] and ''[[ikat]]'' from the [[Lesser Sundas]].  In 1603, an average quality ''[[sarong]]''-sized cloth traded for eighteen kilograms of nutmeg.  Some of these textiles were then on-sold, ending up in [[Halmahera]] and [[New Guinea]].  Coarser ''ikat'' from the Lesser Sundas was traded for [[sago]] from the [[Kei Islands]], [[Aru Islands Regency|Aru]] and [[Seram]].\n\n===Portuguese===\nIn August 1511 on behalf of the king of [[Portugal]], [[Afonso de Albuquerque]] conquered [[Malacca]], which at the time was the hub of Asian trade. In November of that year, after having secured Malacca and learning of the Bandas' location, Albuquerque sent an expedition of three ships led by his good friend [[Ant\u00f3nio de Abreu]] to find them. [[Malay (ethnic group)|Malay]] pilots, either recruited or forcibly conscripted, guided them via [[Java]], the [[Lesser Sundas]] and [[Ambon Island|Ambon]] to Banda, arriving in early 1512.<ref>Hannard (1991), page 7; {{cite book  | last =Milton  | first =Giles  | authorlink =Giles Milton    | title =Nathaniel's Nutmeg  | publisher =Sceptre  | year =1999  | location =London  | pages =5 and 7  | isbn = 978-0-340-69676-7 }}</ref> The first Europeans to reach the Bandas, the expedition remained in Banda for about one month, purchasing and filling their ships with Banda's nutmeg and mace, and with [[clove]]s in which Banda had a thriving entrep\u00f4t trade.<ref name=\"HANNARDp7\">Hannard (1991), page 7</ref> D'Abreu sailed through [[Ambon Island|Ambon]] and [[Seram Island|Seram]] while his second in command [[Francisco Serr\u00e3o]] went ahead towards the Maluku islands, was shipwrecked and ended up in [[Ternate]].<ref name=\"RICKLEFSp25\"/> Distracted by hostilities elsewhere in the archipelago, such as Ambon and Ternate, the Portuguese did not return until 1529; a Portuguese trader Captain Garcia Henriques landed troops in the Bandas. Five of the Banda islands were within gunshot of each other and he realised that a fort on the main island Neira would give him full control of the group. The Bandanese were, however, hostile to such a plan, and their warlike antics were both costly and tiresome to Garcia whose men were attacked when they attempted to build a fort. From then on, the Portuguese were infrequent visitors to the islands preferring to buy their nutmeg from traders in Malacca.<ref>{{cite book  | last =Milton  | first =Giles  | authorlink =Giles Milton    | title =Nathaniel's Nutmeg  | publisher =Sceptre  | year =1999  | location =London  | pages =5 and 7  | isbn = 978-0-340-69676-7 }}</ref>\n\nUnlike other eastern Indonesian islands, such as [[Ambon Island|Ambon]], [[Solor]], [[Ternate]] and [[Morotai]], the Bandanese displayed no enthusiasm for Christianity or the Europeans who brought it in the sixteenth century, and no serious attempt was made to Christianise the Bandanese.<ref name=\"RICKLEFSp25\">{{cite book  | last =Ricklefs  | first =M.C. | title =A History of Modern Indonesia Since c.1300, 2nd Edition  | publisher =MacMillan  | year =1993  | location =London  | page =25 | isbn = 978-0-333-57689-2 }}</ref> Maintaining their independence, the Bandanese never allowed the Portuguese to build a fort or a permanent post in the islands. Ironically though, it was this lack of ports which brought the Dutch to trade at Banda instead of the clove islands of Ternate and Tidore.\n\n===Dutch Control===\n{{main|Governorate of the Banda Islands}}\n[[File:Fort Nassau 1646.jpg|right|thumb|[[Fort Nassau, Banda Islands|Fort Nassau]] in 1646]]\n\nThe Dutch followed the Portuguese to Banda but were to have a much more dominating and lasting presence. Dutch-Bandanese relations were mutually resentful from the outset, with Holland's first merchants complaining of Bandanese reneging on agreed deliveries and price, and cheating on quantity and quality. For the Bandanese, on the other hand, although they welcomed another competitor purchaser for their spices, the items of trade offered by the Dutch\u2014heavy woolens, and damasks, unwanted manufactured goods, for example\u2014were usually unsuitable in comparison to traditional trade products. The [[Javanese people|Javanese]], [[Arab]] and [[India]]n, and Portuguese traders for example brought indispensable items along with steel knives, copper, medicines and prized [[China|Chinese]] [[porcelain]].{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nAs much as the Dutch disliked dealing with the Bandanese, the trade was a highly profitable one with spices selling for 300 times the purchase price in Banda. This amply justified the expense and risk in shipping them to Europe. The allure of such profits saw an increasing number of Dutch expeditions; it was soon seen that in trade with the East Indies, competition from each would eat into all their profits. Thus the competitors united to form the ''Vereenigde Oostindische Compagnie (VOC)'' (the \u2018[[Dutch East Indies Company]]) in 1602.<ref name = \"uclwxl\">Hannard (1991)</ref>\n\nUntil the early seventeenth century the Bandas were ruled by a group of leading citizens, the ''orang kaya'' (literally 'rich men'); each of these was head of a district. At the time nutmeg was one of the \"fine spices\" kept expensive in Europe by disciplined manipulation of the market, but a desirable commodity for Dutch traders in the ports of India as well; economic historian [[Fernand Braudel]] notes that India consumed twice as much as Europe.<ref>Braudel 1984, p. 219</ref> A number of Banda's ''orang kaya'' were persuaded by the Dutch to sign a treaty granting the Dutch a monopoly on spice purchases. Even though the Bandanese had little understanding of the significance of the treaty known as 'The Eternal Compact', or that not all Bandanese leaders had signed, it would later be used to justify Dutch troops being brought in to defend their monopoly.\n\nIn April 1609, Admiral [[Pieter Willemsz. Verhoeff]] arrived at Banda Neira with a request by [[Maurice, Prince of Orange]] to build a fort on the island (the eventual [[Fort Nassau, Banda Islands|Fort Nassau]]). The Bandanese were not excited about this idea. On 22 May, before building of the fort had started, the ''orang kaya'' called a meeting with the Dutch admiral, purportedly to negotiate prices. Instead, they led Verhoeff and two high-ranked men into an ambush and decapitated them and subsequently killed 46 of the Dutch visitors. [[Jan Pietersz Coen]], who was a lower-ranked merchant on the expedition, managed to escape, but the traumatic event likely influenced his future attitude towards the Bandanese.<ref>Opstall, M.E. van, ''De reis van de vloot van Pieter Willemsz Verhoeff naar Azi\u00eb 1607\u20131612'', Utrecht University, 1972, pp. 95\u201398.</ref>\n\n[[File:Fort Belgica 1824.jpg|thumb|Fort Belgica in 1824]]\n\n===English-Dutch rivalry===\nWhile Portuguese and Spanish activity in the region had weakened, the English had built fortified trading posts on tiny Ai and [[Run (island)|Run]] islands, ten to twenty kilometres from the main Banda Islands. With the English paying higher prices, they were significantly undermining Dutch aims for a monopoly. As Anglo-Dutch tensions increased in 1611 the Dutch built the larger and more strategic [[Fort Belgica]] above Fort Nassau.\n\nIn 1615, the Dutch invaded Ai with 900 men whereupon the English retreated to Run where they regrouped. Japanese mercenaries served in the Dutch forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wardsan.travellerspoint.com/s21/|title=Asia 2008\u201309|work=travellerspoint.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.library.utoronto.ca/details?7626150|title=Merchant kings : when companies ruled the world, 1600\u20131900 / \u2013 University of Toronto Libraries|work=utoronto.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danbyrnes.com.au/lostworlds/timeline/lwstory7.htm|title=Lost Worlds Page 7 \u2013 From 1600\u20131700|first=Dan|last=Byrnes|work=danbyrnes.com.au}}</ref> That same night, the English launched a surprise counter-attack on Ai, retaking the island and killing 200 Dutchmen. A year later, a much stronger Dutch force attacked Ai. This time the defenders were able to hold off the attack with cannon fire, but after a month of siege they ran out of ammunition. The Dutch slaughtered the defenders, and afterwards strengthened the fort, renaming it 'Fort Revenge'.\n\n[[File:COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Militairen bij het standbeeld van Koning Willem III op Banda TMnr 10018594.jpg|thumb|upright|Colonial soldiers standing guard next to the statue of [[King Willem III of the Netherlands]], representing [[Dutch empire|Dutch dominance]] on Banda.]]\n\n===Massacre of the Bandanese===\n{{main|Dutch conquest of the Banda Islands}}\nNewly appointed VOC governor-general [[Jan Pieterszoon Coen]] set about enforcing Dutch monopoly over the Banda's spice trade. In 1621 well-armed soldiers were landed on Bandaneira Island and within a few days they had also occupied neighbouring and larger [[Lontar island|Lontar]]. The ''orang kaya'' were forced at gunpoint to sign an unfeasibly arduous treaty, one that was in fact impossible to keep, thus providing Coen an excuse to use superior Dutch force against the Bandanese.<ref name = \"uclwxl\"/> The Dutch quickly noted a number of alleged violations of the new treaty, in response to which Coen launched a punitive massacre. Japanese mercenaries were hired to deal with the ''orang kaya'',<ref>{{cite news |title=The world's oldest clove tree  |author=Simon Worrall |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-18551857 |newspaper=BBC News |date=23 June 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/fooc/2012/07/120706_fooc_oldest_clove_tree.shtml \u8bb0\u8005\u6765\u9e3f\uff1a\u0093\u963f\u548c\u0094\u7684\u4f20\u5947] BBC China</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.matatraders.com/fair-trade-movement/2011/12/reigniting-the-mystique-of-the-%E2%80%98spice-islands%E2%80%99-to-benefit-farmers/|title=Reigniting the Mystique of the 'Spice Islands' to Benefit Farmers|date=16 December 2011|work=matatraders.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://herbicidefree.co/2014/01/18/nothing-changes/|title=Nothing changes|date=18 January 2014|work=herbicidefree.co}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lloydthomas.org/1-IsraelTimeLine/6-1543-1929/1543-1820.htm|title=1542\u20131820 AD/CE|work=lloydthomas.org}}</ref> forty of whom were beheaded with their heads impaled and displayed on bamboo spears.<ref name=\"Unoki2012\">{{cite book|author=Ko Unoki|title=Mergers, Acquisitions and Global Empires: Tolerance, Diversity and the Success of M&A|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6UaeL64p-ukC&pg=PA56|date=12 October 2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-21538-4|page=56}}</ref> The butchering and beheadings were carried out by the Japanese for the Dutch.<ref name=\"Krondl2008\">{{cite book|author=Michael Krondl|title=The Taste of Conquest: The Rise and Fall of the Three Great Cities of Spice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ewNtDrKa5yYC&pg=PT209|date=28 October 2008|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-345-50982-6|page=209}}</ref>\n\nThe islanders were also tortured by the Dutch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2012/11/26/165657050/no-innocent-spice-the-secret-story-of-nutmeg-life-and-death|title=No Innocent Spice: The Secret Story of Nutmeg, Life And Death|work=npr.org}}</ref> The Bandanese chiefs were tortured by the Dutch and Japanese.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nicholas.duke.edu/nature-rambles/frigates-war-canoes-and-volcanoes/|title=Frigates, War Canoes, and Volcanoes|date=26 October 2015|work=duke.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:xTHp2w0IAYwJ:blogs.nicholas.duke.edu/nature-rambles/frigates-war-canoes-and-volcanoes/%20&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us |title=Frigates, War Canoes, and Volcanoes |date=26 October 2015 |work=googleusercontent.com }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nicholas.duke.edu/nature-rambles/environmental-health/feed/|title=environmental health \u2013 Nature Rambles|work=duke.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:1FdHoxLNRnUJ:blogs.nicholas.duke.edu/nature-rambles/environmental-health/feed/%20&cd=2&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us |title=environmental health \u2013 Nature Rambles|work=googleusercontent.com }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"Turner2008\">{{cite book|author=Jack Turner|title=Spice: The History of a Temptation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EzXF7cpeMr0C&pg=PA291|date=10 December 2008|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-49122-0|pages=290\u2013291}}</ref>\n\nThe Dutch carved 68 parcels out of the islands after the enslavement and slaughter of the natives.<ref name=\"PrakWebb2005\">{{cite book|author1=Maarten Prak|author2=Diane Webb|title=The Dutch Republic in the Seventeenth Century: The Golden Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JhIxrykbrKUC&pg=PA119|date=22 September 2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-84352-2|page=119}}</ref><ref name=\"Milton2012\">{{cite book|author=Giles Milton|title=Nathaniel's Nutmeg|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nQ1AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT163|date=12 April 2012|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|isbn=978-1-4447-1771-6|page=163}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/29386.Nathaniel_s_Nutmeg|title=Nathaniel's Nutmeg|work=goodreads.com}}</ref>\n\nThe population of the Banda Islands prior to Dutch conquest is generally estimated to have been around 13,000\u201315,000 people, some of whom were Malay and Javanese traders, as well as Chinese and Arabs. The actual numbers of Bandanese who were killed, forcibly expelled or fled the islands in 1621 remain uncertain. But readings of historical sources suggest around one thousand Bandanese likely survived in the islands, and were spread throughout the nutmeg groves as forced labourers.<ref>Hanna 1991, p.54; Loth 1995, p.18</ref><ref name=\"Tarling1999\">{{cite book|author=Nicholas Tarling|authorlink=Nicholas Tarling|title=The Cambridge History of Southeast Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GIz4CDTCOwcC&pg=PA86|year=1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-66370-0|pages=86\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Tarling1992\">{{cite book|author=Nicholas Tarling|title=The Cambridge History of Southeast Asia: Volume 1, From Early Times to C.1800|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rOw8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA430|year=1992|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-35505-6|pages=430\u2013}}</ref> The Dutch subsequently re-settled the islands with imported slaves, convicts and indentured labourers (to work the nutmeg plantations), as well as immigrants from elsewhere in Indonesia. Most survivors fled as refugees to the islands of their trading partners, in particular [[Keffing]] and [[Guli Guli]] in the [[Seram|Seram Laut]] chain and [[Kei Islands|Kei Besar]].<ref name = \"uclwxl\"/> Shipments of surviving Bandanese were also sent to Batavia ([[Jakarta]]) to work as slaves in developing the city and its fortress. Some 530 of these individuals were later returned to the islands because of their much-needed expertise in nutmeg cultivation (something sorely lacking among newly arrived Dutch settlers).<ref>Hanna 1991, p.55; Loth 1995, p.24</ref>\n\nWhereas up until this point the Dutch presence had been simply as traders, that was sometimes treaty-based, the Banda conquest marked the start of the first overt colonial rule in Indonesia, albeit under the auspices of the VOC.\n\n===VOC Monopoly===\n[[File:Banda Neira 1724.jpg|thumb|Banda Neira in 1724]]\n\nHaving nearly eradicated the islands' native population, Coen divided the productive land of approximately half a million nutmeg trees into sixty-eight 1.2-hectare ''perken''. These land parcels were then handed to Dutch planters known as ''perkeniers'' of which 34 were on [[Lontar island|Lontar]], 31 on Ai and 3 on Neira.  With few Bandanese left to work them, slaves from elsewhere were brought in.<ref name=\"Brown2004\">{{cite book|author=Iem Brown|title=The Territories of Indonesia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lfPJAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA260|date=17 June 2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-35541-8|page=170}}</ref> Now enjoying control of the nutmeg production, the VOC paid the ''perkeniers'' 1/122nd of the Dutch market price for nutmeg; however, the ''perkeniers'' still profited immensely building substantial villas with opulent imported European decorations.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nThe outlying island of Run was harder for the VOC to control and they exterminated all nutmeg trees there. The production and export of nutmeg was a VOC monopoly for almost two hundred years. [[Fort Belgica]], one of many forts built by the [[Dutch East India Company]], is one of the largest remaining European forts in Indonesia.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\n===English-Dutch rivalry continues===\n{{further|Invasion of the Spice Islands}}\nThough not physically present at the Banda Islands, the English claimed the small island of [[Run (island)|Run]] until 1667 when, under the [[Treaty of Breda (1667)]], the Dutch and English agreed to maintain the colonial [[status quo]] and relinquish their respective claims.\n[[File:Banda1810Cole.jpg|thumb|View of the Island of Banda-Neira captured by the British on 9 August 1810]]\n\nIn 1810, the Kingdom of Holland was a vassal of Napoleonic France and hence in conflict with Britain.  The French and British were each seeking to control lucrative Indian Ocean trade routes.  On 10 May 1810, a squadron consisting of the 36-gun frigate {{HMS|Caroline}}, [[French frigate Pi\u00e9montaise (1804)|HMS ''Piedmontaise'']], formerly a French frigate, 18-gun [[Cruizer class brig-sloop|sloop]] {{HMS|Barracouta}}, and the 12-gun transport {{HMS|Mandarin|1810|6}} left [[Chennai|Madras]] with money, supplies and troops to support the garrison at [[Ambon Island|Amboyna]], recently captured from the Dutch.  The frigates and sloop carried a hundred officers and men of the [[102nd Regiment of Foot (Royal Madras Fusiliers)|Madras European Regiment]], while the ''Mandarin'' carried supplies.  The squadron was commanded by Captain [[Christopher Cole (Royal Navy officer)|Christopher Cole]], with Captain Charles Foote on the ''Piedmontaise'' and Captain Richard Kenah aboard the ''Barracouta''.  After departing from Madras, Cole informed Foote and Kenah of Cole's plan to capture the Bandas; Foote and Kenah agreed. In Singapore, Captain [[Richard Spencer (Royal Navy officer)|Spencer]] informed Cole that over 700 regular Dutch troops may be located in the Bandas.<ref name=\"Adkins\">{{cite book |last1=Adkins |first1=Roy |last2=Adkins |first2=Lesley |title=The War for All the Oceans: From Nelson at the Nile to Napoleon at Waterloo |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3u9jdSlnGiMC&pg=PA345|year=2008 |publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-0-14-311392-8 |pages=344\u2013355}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Annual biography and obituary |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h-UKAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA114|volume=21 |year=1837 |publisher=Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme, and Brown |location=London |pages=114\u2013123 |chapter=Sir Christopher Cole, K.C.B. }}</ref>\n\nThe squadron took a circuitous route to avoid alerting the Dutch.  On 9 August 1810, the British appeared at [[Banda Neira]].  They quickly stormed the island and attacked [[Fort Belgica|Belgica Castle]] at sunrise.  The battle was over within hours, with the Dutch surrendering [[Fort Nassau, Banda Islands|Fort Nassau]] \u2013 after some subterfuge \u2013 and within days the remainder of the Banda Islands. After the Dutch surrender, Captain Charles Foote (of the ''Piedmontaise'') was appointed Lieutenant-Governor of the Banda Islands. This action was a prelude to Britain's [[Invasion of Java (1811)|invasion of Java]] in 1811.<ref name=\"Adkins\" />\n\nBefore the Dutch retook control of the islands, the British removed many nutmeg trees and transplanted them to [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]] and other British colonies.  The competition largely destroyed the value of the Banda Islands to the Dutch.<ref>{{cite news |title=Banda, the nutmeg treasure islands |first=Peter |last=Milne |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/01/16/banda-nutmeg-treasure-islands.html |newspaper=Jakarta Post |location=Jakarta |date=16 January 2011 |pages=10\u201311 |accessdate=22 December 2011 |quote=But the economic importance of the Bandas was only fleeting. With the Napoleonic wars raging across Europe, the English returned to the Bandas in the early 19th century, temporarily taking over control from the Dutch. This gave the English an opportunity to uproot hundreds of valuable nutmeg seedlings and transport them to their own colonies in Ceylon and Singapore, breaking forever the Dutch monopoly and consigning the Bandas to economic decline and irrelevance.}}</ref>\n\n===Recent history===\nIn the late 1990s, violence between Christians and Muslims and between indigenous locals and [[Transmigration program|transmigrants]] spilled over from [[Maluku sectarian conflict|intercommunal conflict]] in Ambon. The disturbance and resulting deaths damaged the previously prosperous [[tourism]] industry.<ref>Witton, Patrick (2003). Indonesia. Melbourne: Lonely Planet. {{ISBN|1-74059-154-2}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThere are seven inhabited islands and several that are uninhabited.  The inhabited islands are:\n[[File:BandaVolcano.JPG|thumb|The active volcano [[Banda Api]] in the Banda Islands]]\n[[File:Banda-0039.jpg|thumb|The main island, Banda Neira (centre) viewed from the peak of Gunung Api volcano. In the background is [[Lontar Island]] (Banda Besar).]]\nMain group:\n*[[Banda Neira]], or Naira, the island with the administrative capital and a small airfield (as well as accommodation for visitors). Present on Banda Neira is Fort Belgica, one of the largest remaining Dutch forts that are still intact in Indonesia. \n*[[Banda Api]], an active volcano (Gunung Api) with a peak of about 650 m\n*Banda Besar is the largest island (Indonesian ''besar'', big), {{convert|12|km|0|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|3|km|0|abbr=on}} wide. It has three main settlements, Lonthoir, Selamon and Waer.\n\nSome distance to the west:\n*Pulau [[Ai (island)|Ai]] or Pulau Ay\n*Pulau [[Run (island)|Run]], further west again. In the 17th century, this island was involved in an exchange between the British and the Dutch: it was exchanged for the island of Manhattan in New York.\n\nTo the east:\n*[[Pisang Island (Maluku)|Pulau Pisang]] (Banana Island), also known as Syahrir.\n\nTo the southeast:\n*Pulau Hatta, formerly Rosengain or Rozengain\n\nOthers, possibly small and/or uninhabited, are:\n*Nailaka, a short distance northeast of Pulau [[Run (island)|Run]]\n*Batu Kapal\n*Manuk, an active volcano\n*Pulau Keraka or Pulau Karaka (Crab Island)\n*Manukang\n*Hatta Reef\n\nThe islands are part of the [[Banda Sea Islands moist deciduous forests]] [[ecoregion]].\n\n==Bandanese culture==\nMost of the present-day inhabitants of the Banda Islands are descended from migrants and plantation labourers from various parts of Indonesia, as well as from indigenous Bandanese. They have inherited aspects of pre-colonial ritual practices in the Bandas that are highly valued and still performed, giving them a distinct and very local cultural identity.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lape|first1=Peter V.|title=Political dynamics and religious change in the late pre-colonial Banda Islands, Eastern Indonesia|journal=World Archaeology|date=2000|volume=32|issue=1|pages=138\u2013155|doi=10.1080/004382400409934|citeseerx=10.1.1.500.4009}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Bandanese speak a distinct dialect of [[Malay language]] which has several features distinguishing it from [[Ambonese Malay]], the better-known and more widespread dialect that forms a lingua franca in central and southeast Maluku. Bandanese Malay is famous in the region for its unique, lilting accent, but it also has a number of locally identifying words in its lexicon, many of them borrowings or [[loanwords]] from [[Dutch language|Dutch]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Winn|first1=Phillip|title=Slavery and cultural creativity in the Banda Islands|journal=Journal of Southeast Asian Studies|date=2010|volume=41|issue=3|pages=365\u2013389|doi=10.1017/s0022463410000238}}</ref>\n\nExamples :\n* fork\t: forok (Dutch vork)\n* ant\t: mir (Dutch mier)\n* spoon\t: lepe (Dutch lepel)\n* difficult : lastek (Dutch lastig)\n* floor : plur (Dutch vloer)\n* porch: stup (Dutch stoep)\n\nBanda Malay shares many [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] loanwords with Ambonese Malay not appearing in the national language, [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]. But it has comparatively fewer, and they differ in pronunciation.\n\nExamples :\n* turtle : tetaruga (Banda Malay); totoruga (Ambonese Malay) (from Portuguese tartaruga)\n* throat : gargontong (Banda Malay); gargangtang (Ambonese Malay) (from Portuguese garganta)\n\nFinally, and most noticeably, Banda Malay uses some distinct pronouns. The most immediately distinguishing is that of the second person singular familiar form of address: pan\u00e9.\n\nThe descendants of some of the Bandanese who fled Dutch conquest in the seventeenth century live in the [[Kai Islands]] (Kepulauan Kei) to the east of the Banda group, where a version of the original [[Banda language (Indonesia)|Banda language]] is still spoken in the villages of Banda Eli and Banda Elat on Kai Besar Island. While long integrated into Kei Island society, residents of these settlements continue to value the historical origins of their ancestors.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Indonesia}}\n*[[1938 Banda Sea earthquake]]\n*[[Dutch East India Company in Indonesia]]\n*[[History of Indonesia]]\n*[[List of earthquakes in Indonesia]]\n*[[List of volcanoes in Indonesia#Banda Sea]]\n*[[Maluku Islands]]\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Giles Milton]]. ''[[Nathaniel's Nutmeg]]: How One Man's Courage Changed the Course of History'' (Sceptre books, Hodder and Stoughton, London)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*Braudel, Fernand. 1984. The Perspective of the World. In: ''Civilization and Capitalism'', vol. III.\n*{{cite book  | last =  Hanna| first =Willard A.| title =Indonesian Banda: Colonialism and its Aftermath in the Nutmeg Islands| publisher =Yayasan Warisan dan Budaya Banda Naira  | year =1991| location =[[Bandanaira]] }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Lape | first1 = Peter | year = 2000 | title = Political dynamics and religious change in the late pre-colonial Banda Islands, Eastern Indonesia | journal = World Archaeology | volume = 32 | issue = 1| pages = 138\u2013155 | doi=10.1080/004382400409934| citeseerx = 10.1.1.500.4009 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Loth | first1 = Vincent C | year = 1995 | title = Pioneers and perkerniers:the Banda Islands in the seventeenth century | journal = Cakalele | volume = 6 | pages = 13\u201335 }}\n*{{cite book  | last =  Muller| first =Karl |author2=Pickell, David (ed)| title =Maluku: Indonesian Spice Islands  | publisher =Periplus Editions  | year =1997  | location =Singapore | isbn = 978-962-593-176-0 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Villiers | first1 = John | year = 1981 | title = Trade and society in the Banda Islands in the sixteenth century | journal = Modern Asian Studies | volume = 15 | issue = 4| pages = 723\u2013750 | doi=10.1017/s0026749x0000874x}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Winn | first1 = Phillip | year = 1998 | title = Banda is the Blessed Land: sacred practice and identity in the Banda Islands, Maluku | journal = Antropologi Indonesia | volume = 57 | pages = 71\u201380 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Winn | first1 = Phillip | year = 2001 | title = Graves, groves and gardens: place and identity in central Maluku, Indonesia| journal = The Asia Pacific Journal of Anthropology | volume = 2 | issue = 1| pages = 24\u201344 | doi=10.1080/14442210110001706025}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Winn | first1 = Phillip | year = 2002 | title = Everyone searches, everyone finds: moral discourse and resource use in an Indonesian Muslim community | journal = Oceania | volume = 72 | issue = 4| pages = 275\u2013292 | doi=10.1002/j.1834-4461.2002.tb02796.x}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Banda Islands}}\n{{wikivoyage|Banda Islands}}\n*{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Banda Islands |volume=3 |short=x}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090302023256/http://www.royal-navy.org/lib/index.php?title=Capture_of_Banda_Neira Capture of Banda Neira by the British Royal Navy 1810]\n*{{WWF ecoregion|name=Banda Sea Islands moist deciduous forests|id=aa0102}}\n*[http://www.spiceislandsforts.com/the-bandas/ Forts of the Spice Islands]\n\n{{Maluku-islands}}\n{{Dutch colonies|East India}}\n\n[[Category:Portuguese colonialism in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Dutch East India Company]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Maluku (province)]]\n[[Category:Volcanic groups]]\n[[Category:Banda Sea]]\n[[Category:Banda Islands| ]]\n[[Category:Central Maluku Regency]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banda_Islands"}
{"title_page": "Banda Arc", "text_new": "[[File:Banda Arc tectonic map.jpg|thumb|Banda Arc tectonic map]]\n\nThe '''Banda Arc''' (main arc, Inner, and Outer) is a set of [[island arcs]] that exist in eastern [[Indonesia]]. It manifests the collision of a [[continent]] and an intra-oceanic [[island arc]]. The presently active arc is located on what appears to be [[oceanic crust]] whereas the associated [[subduction]] trench is underlain by [[continental crust]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Origin of late-cenozoic lavas from the Banda arc, Indonesia: Trace element and Sr isotope evidence|author1=D. J. Whitford |author2=P. A. Jezek |doi=10.1007/BF00371896 |bibcode=1979CoMP...68..141W |volume=68 |issue = 2|journal=Contributions to Mineralogy and Petrology |pages=141\u2013150|year = 1979}}</ref> The convergence of the Indo-Australian [[Plate tectonics|plates]] and [[Eurasia]] and resulted in the formation of the Sunda and Banda [[island arc]]s. The transitional zone between the arcs is located south of [[Flores|Flores Island]] and is characterized by the change in the [[Tectonics|tectonic]] regime along the boundary.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = Sunda-Banda arc transition, Incipient continent-island arc collision (northwest Australia)|author1=A. Shulgin |author2=H. Kopp |author3=C. Mueller |author4=E. Lueschen |author5=L. Planert |author6=M. Engels |author7=E. R. Flueh |author8=A. Krabbenhoeft |author9=Y. Djajadihardja  |last-author-amp=yes |date = May 27, 2009|journal = Geophysical Research Letters|volume = 36|issue = 10|pages = L10304|doi = 10.1029/2009gl037533|pmid = |access-date = |bibcode = 2009GeoRL..3610304S}}</ref>\n\n== Terminology ==\nSome academic literature refers to the arcs by location \u2013 so that main arc can be referred to as the 'southern',<ref>{{Citation | author1=Ely, Kim Susan | title=Geochronology of Timor-Leste and seismo-tectonics of the southern Banda Arc | date=2009 | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/37054964 | accessdate=21 December 2014 }}</ref> the 'western' <ref>{{Citation | author1=Chamalaun, F. H | author2=Sunata, Wahyu | author3=Institute for Australasian Geodynamics | author4=Flinders University. School of Earth Sciences | author5=Workshop on Palaeomagnetic Research in Southeast and East Asia (1982 : Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia) | title=Progress report on the paleomagnetism of the Western Banda Arc system | date=1982 | publisher=Institute for Australasian Geodynamics | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/8321009 | accessdate=21 December 2014 }}</ref> Situated at the centre of three converging and colliding major [[Plate tectonics|tectonic plates]], [[Indo-Australian Plate|Indo-Australia]], [[Eurasia]], [[Pacific Plate|Pacific]], the Banda arc comprises young [[oceanic crust]] enclosed by a [[Volcanic arc|volcanic inner arc]], outer arc islands and a trough parallel to the Australian [[continental margin]]. It is a complex [[subduction]] setting (where one plate moves under another, sinking into the Earth's [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]]), with possibly the largest fold on [[Earth]], extending to a depth of about {{convert|650|km|0|abbr=on}}, in a subducted plate.<ref>{{Cite news|url = |title = Indonesia's puzzling Banda arc: New findings explain mystery behind geological development|last = University of Royal Holloway London|first = |date = July 27, 2010|work = |access-date = |via = }}</ref>\n\n== Inner/Outer ==\n[[File:Banda-arc-cross-section.jpg|thumb|Cross section between inner and outer arc]]\nThe '''Banda Arc''' is a double [[island arc]] formed by the collision of the [[Indo-Australian plate]] with the [[Eurasian plate]]. Principal islands include [[Timor]], [[Flores]], and [[Seram Island|Seram]].\n* The '''Inner Banda Arc''' consists of a string of recent and active volcanic islands from [[Komodo Island|Komodo]] to [[Kekeh-besar]] of the [[Barat Daya Islands]], including Flores, [[Solor Archipelago|Solor]], [[Alor Archipelago|Alor]], [[Wetar]], and [[Damar Island|Damar]].\n* The '''Outer Banda Arc''' is older and non-volcanic. It overlies the margin of the Pre-Cambrian [[craton]] that makes up much of the continent of Australia. It stretches from [[Savu Island|Savu]] through [[Rote Island|Rote]], [[Timor]], [[Leti Islands|Leti]], [[Babar Islands|Babar]], [[Tanimbar Islands|Tanimbar]], and the [[Kai Islands]], before turning west to [[Seram Island|Seram]], [[Ambon Island|Ambon]], and [[Buru Island|Buru]]. The outer arc is geologically associated with the Australian continent, though it is a more recent accretion than the neighbouring [[Aru Islands]].\n\nThe feature they apparently formed is a 180-degree [[Island arc|arc]], which is more than {{convert|1,000|km|mi|abbr=off}} long. Geographically, it stretches across eastern [[Indonesia]], and is delimited by an active inner [[Volcano|volcanic]] arc. The outer arc contains numerous [[island]]s, and its internal [[Structure of the Earth|structure]] contains young [[oceanic crust]] exclusively.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://news.softpedia.com/news/Origins-of-the-Banda-Arc-Explained-151114.shtml|title = Origins of the Banda Arc Explained|last = Tudor Vieru|date = 6 Aug 2010|work = |access-date = |via = }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{wikibooks|The Geology of Indonesia/Banda Arc}}\n* [[Banda Sea Plate]]\n* [[Islands of Indonesia]]\n* [[Oceanic trench]]\n* [[Plate tectonic]]\n* [[Sunda Arc]]\n* [[Sunda Islands]]\n** [[Greater Sunda Islands]]\n** [[Lesser Sunda Islands]]\n* [[Sundaland]]\n* [[Sunda Trench]]\n* [[Weber Deep]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Audley-Charles | first1 = MG | year = 1986 | title = Timor\u2013Tanimbar Trough: the foreland basin of the evolving Banda orogen | url = | journal = Spec. Publs Int. Ass. Sediment | volume = 8 | issue = | pages = 91\u2013102 }}\n\n{{coord|8.9827|S|125.3210|E|source:wikidata-and-enwiki-cat-tree_region:ID|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Plate tectonics]]\n[[Category:Island arcs]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Arcs of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Outer Banda Arc| ]]\n[[Category:Inner Banda Arc| ]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Banda Arc tectonic map.jpg|thumb|Banda Arc tectonic map]]\n\nThe '''Banda Arc''' (main arc, Inner, and Outer) is a set of [[island arcs]] that exist in eastern [[Indonesia]]. It manifests the collision of a [[continent]] and an intra-oceanic [[island arc]]. The presently active arc is located on what appears to be [[oceanic crust]] whereas the associated [[subduction]] trench is underlain by [[continental crust]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Origin of late-cenozoic lavas from the Banda arc, Indonesia: Trace element and Sr isotope evidence|author1=D. J. Whitford |author2=P. A. Jezek |doi=10.1007/BF00371896 |bibcode=1979CoMP...68..141W |volume=68 |issue = 2|journal=Contributions to Mineralogy and Petrology |pages=141\u2013150|year = 1979}}</ref> The convergence of the Indo-Australian [[Plate tectonics|plates]] and [[Eurasia]] and resulted in the formation of the Sunda and Banda [[island arc]]s. The transitional zone between the arcs is located south of [[Flores|Flores Island]] and is characterized by the change in the [[Tectonics|tectonic]] regime along the boundary.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = Sunda-Banda arc transition, Incipient continent-island arc collision (northwest Australia)|author1=A. Shulgin |author2=H. Kopp |author3=C. Mueller |author4=E. Lueschen |author5=L. Planert |author6=M. Engels |author7=E. R. Flueh |author8=A. Krabbenhoeft |author9=Y. Djajadihardja  |last-author-amp=yes |date = May 27, 2009|journal = Geophysical Research Letters|volume = 36|issue = 10|pages = L10304|doi = 10.1029/2009gl037533|pmid = |access-date = |bibcode = 2009GeoRL..3610304S}}</ref>\n\n== Terminology ==\nSome academic literature refers to the arcs by location \u2013 so that main arc can be referred to as the 'southern',<ref>{{Citation | author1=Ely, Kim Susan | title=Geochronology of Timor-Leste and seismo-tectonics of the southern Banda Arc | date=2009 | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/37054964 | accessdate=21 December 2014 }}</ref> the 'western' <ref>{{Citation | author1=Chamalaun, F. H | author2=Sunata, Wahyu | author3=Institute for Australasian Geodynamics | author4=Flinders University. School of Earth Sciences | author5=Workshop on Palaeomagnetic Research in Southeast and East Asia (1982 : Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia) | title=Progress report on the paleomagnetism of the Western Banda Arc system | date=1982 | publisher=Institute for Australasian Geodynamics | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/8321009 | accessdate=21 December 2014 }}</ref> Situated at the centre of three converging and colliding major [[Plate tectonics|tectonic plates]], [[Indo-Australian Plate|Indo-Australia]], [[Eurasia]], [[Pacific Plate|Pacific]], the Banda arc comprises young [[oceanic crust]] enclosed by a [[Volcanic arc|volcanic inner arc]], outer arc islands and a trough parallel to the Australian [[continental margin]]. It is a complex [[subduction]] setting (where one plate moves under another, sinking into the Earth's [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]]), with possibly the largest fold on [[Earth]], extending to a depth of about {{convert|650|km|0|abbr=on}}, in a subducted plate.<ref>{{Cite news|url = |title = Indonesia's puzzling Banda arc: New findings explain mystery behind geological development|last = University of Royal Holloway London|first = |date = July 27, 2010|work = |access-date = |via = }}</ref>\n\n== Inner/Outer ==\n[[File:Banda-arc-cross-section.jpg|thumb|Cross section between inner and outer arc]]\nThe '''Banda Arc''' is a double [[island arc]] formed by the collision of the [[Indo-Australian plate]] with the [[Eurasian plate]]. Principal islands include [[Timor]], [[Flores]], and [[Seram Island|Seram]].\n* The '''Inner Banda Arc''' consists of a string of recent and active volcanic islands from [[Komodo Island|Komodo]] to [[Kekeh-besar]] of the [[Barat Daya Islands]], including Flores, [[Solor Archipelago|Solor]], [[Alor Archipelago|Alor]], [[Wetar]], and [[Damar Island|Damar]].\n* The '''Outer Banda Arc''' is older and non-volcanic. It overlies the margin of the Pre-Cambrian [[craton]] that makes up much of the continent of Australia. It stretches from [[Savu Island|Savu]] through [[Rote Island|Rote]], [[Timor]], [[Leti Islands|Leti]], [[Babar Islands|Babar]], [[Tanimbar Islands|Tanimbar]], and the [[Kai Islands]], before turning west to [[Seram Island|Seram]], [[Ambon Island|Ambon]], and [[Buru Island|Buru]]. The outer arc is geologically associated with the Australian continent, though it is a more recent accretion than the neighbouring [[Aru Islands]].\n\nThe feature they apparently formed is a 180-degree [[Island arc|arc]], which is more than {{convert|1,000|km|mi|abbr=off}} long. Geographically, it stretches across eastern [[Indonesia]], and is delimited by an active inner [[Volcano|volcanic]] arc. The outer arc contains numerous [[island]]s, and its internal [[Structure of the Earth|structure]] contains young [[oceanic crust]] exclusively.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://news.softpedia.com/news/Origins-of-the-Banda-Arc-Explained-151114.shtml|title = Origins of the Banda Arc Explained|last = Tudor Vieru|date = 6 Aug 2010|work = |access-date = |via = }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{wikibooks|The Geology of Indonesia/Banda Arc}}\n* [[Banda Sea Plate]]\n* [[Islands of Indonesia]]\n* [[Oceanic trench]]\n* [[Plate tectonic]]\n* [[Sunda Arc]]\n* [[Sunda Islands]]\n** [[Greater Sunda Islands]]\n** [[Lesser Sunda Islands]]\n* [[Sundaland]]\n* [[Sunda Trench]]\n* [[Weber Deep]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Audley-Charles | first1 = MG | year = 1986 | title = Timor\u2013Tanimbar Trough: the foreland basin of the evolving Banda orogen | url = | journal = Spec. Publs Int. Ass. Sediment | volume = 8 | issue = | pages = 91\u2013102 }}\n\n{{coord|8.9827|S|125.3210|E|source:wikidata-and-enwiki-cat-tree_region:ID|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Plate tectonics]]\n[[Category:Island arcs]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Arcs of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Outer Banda Arc| ]]\n[[Category:Inner Banda Arc| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banda_Arc"}
{"title_page": "Balabalagan Islands", "text_new": "'''Balabalagan Islands''' (also spelled '''Bala Balakang''' and historically known as '''Little Paternoster Islands''') are an archipelago and a subdistrict of [[Mamuju Regency]] located in the [[Makassar Strait]] off the east coast of [[Kalimantan]] (Borneo), halfway between it and [[Sulawesi]], [[Indonesia]]. The archipelago is also located near the geographic center of Indonesia.\n\nIn the 19th century, the islands were recorded as numbering 14, with the largest named Sebunkatang; the channels were shallow and unnavigable, but provided a fertile fishing ground for the island natives, called [[Bajaw people|Biajoo]].<ref>{{cite book\n|url=https://archive.org/details/anewandcomprehe02wriggoog\n|page=[https://archive.org/details/anewandcomprehe02wriggoog/page/n445 384]\n|quote=balabalagan.\n|title=A New and Comprehensive Gazetteer\n|author=George Wright\n|year=1834\n|publisher=Thomas Kelly}}</ref> The islands rest on a [[coral reef]], itself placed on an undersea bank which extends out from Kalimantan, presenting a major hazard to navigation; the ''Admiralty Pilot'' has warned that \"No vessel should venture among [them] without local knowledge.\"<ref>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hM-9joPZMj8C&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=%22little+paternoster+islands%22&source=web&ots=S_nIXdIVYw&sig=KLAbS36K9jDuItv9P8kUMMlZXDE\n|title=International Straits of the World: Malacca Singapore and Indonesia\n|author=Michael Leifer\n|year=n.d.\n|publisher=Sijthoff & Nordhoff}} Note that Google Books has mislabeled book.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.mapplanet.com/?do=loc&country=ID&adm1=14&loc=5342564 List of alternate names]\n{{coord|2|27|58.5|S|117|59|46|E|region:ID_type:islands|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Districts of West Sulawesi]]\n[[Category:Landforms of West Sulawesi]]\n[[Category:Underwater diving sites in Indonesia]]\n", "text_old": "'''Balabalagan Islands''' (also spelled '''Bala Balakang''' and historically known as '''Little Paternoster Islands''') are an archipelago and a subdistrict of [[Mamuju Regency]] located in the [[Makassar Strait]] off the east coast of [[Kalimantan]] (Borneo), halfway between it and [[Sulawesi]], [[Indonesia]]. The archipelago is also located near the geographic center of Indonesia.\n\nIn the 19th century, the islands were recorded as numbering 14, with the largest named Sebunkatang; the channels were shallow and unnavigable, but provided a fertile fishing ground for the island natives, called [[Bajaw people|Biajoo]].<ref>{{cite book\n|url=https://archive.org/details/anewandcomprehe02wriggoog\n|page=[https://archive.org/details/anewandcomprehe02wriggoog/page/n445 384]\n|quote=balabalagan.\n|title=A New and Comprehensive Gazetteer\n|author=George Wright\n|year=1834\n|publisher=Thomas Kelly}}</ref> The islands rest on a [[coral reef]], itself placed on an undersea bank which extends out from Kalimantan, presenting a major hazard to navigation; the ''Admiralty Pilot'' has warned that \"No vessel should venture among [them] without local knowledge.\"<ref>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hM-9joPZMj8C&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=%22little+paternoster+islands%22&source=web&ots=S_nIXdIVYw&sig=KLAbS36K9jDuItv9P8kUMMlZXDE\n|title=International Straits of the World: Malacca Singapore and Indonesia\n|author=Michael Leifer\n|year=n.d.\n|publisher=Sijthoff & Nordhoff}} Note that Google Books has mislabeled book.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.mapplanet.com/?do=loc&country=ID&adm1=14&loc=5342564 List of alternate names]\n{{coord|2|27|58.5|S|117|59|46|E|region:ID_type:islands|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Districts of West Sulawesi]]\n[[Category:Landforms of West Sulawesi]]\n[[Category:Underwater diving sites in Indonesia]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balabalagan_Islands"}
{"title_page": "2014 Brazilian economic crisis", "text_new": "{{short description|Crisis that began during the presidency of Dilma Rousseff}}\n{{Copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Brazil's fall (The Economist).jpg|thumb|January 2016 cover of ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine about the crisis. The cover depicts then-president Dilma Rousseff.]]\n\nFrom mid-2014 onward, [[Brazil]] experienced a severe [[financial crisis#Wider economic crisis|economic crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/michel-temer-signs-security-decree-stem-rio-violence-180216183747559.html|title=Michel Temer signs security decree to stem Rio violence|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Barua |first1=Akrur |title=Brazil: Yearning for the good times |url=http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |series=Global Economic Outlook, Q2 2016 |publisher=Deloitte University Press |accessdate=21 May 2016 |date=29 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823114946/http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |archive-date=23 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The country's [[gross domestic product|Gross Domestic Product]] (GDP) fell by 3.5% in 2015 and 3.3% in 2016, after which an economic recovery began.\n\nThe economic crisis occurred alongside a political crisis that resulted in the impeachment of former president [[Dilma Rousseff]]. Together these events caused mass popular dissatisfaction with the political system. In the first quarter of 2017, Brazil's GDP rose by 1%. This was the first GDP increase to occur in eight consecutive quarters. Finance Minister [[Henrique Meirelles]] announced that Brazil had \"emerged from the greatest crisis of the century\". <ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-03/08/c_136110450.htm |title=Brazil GDP falls by 3.6 percent in 2016 |author=Mu Xuequan |date=March 8, 2017}}</ref> However, the rise in GDP marked only the end of a technical recession, not the end of the crisis.\n\nDuring the economic crisis, high unemployment rates were reported throughout the country, and there was widespread uncertainty regarding Brazil's economic future following a series of political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|date=2017-06-01|author=Darlan Alvarenga|accessdate=5 June 2017|work=G1}}</ref> The [[recession]] was the second most severe in the country's [[economic history of Brazil|history]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,com-revisao-ultima-recessao-deixa-de-ser-a-maior-da-historia,70002628638|title=Com revis\u00e3o, \u00faltima recess\u00e3o deixa de ser a maior da hist\u00f3ria |work=Estad\u00e3o|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=1 December 2018|author=Vinicius Neder}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/estagnacao-recessao-ou-depressao-pib-confirma-retomada-mais-fraca-das-ultimas-decadas-23704758|title=Estagna\u00e7\u00e3o, recess\u00e3o ou depress\u00e3o? PIB confirma retomada mais fraca das \u00faltimas d\u00e9cadas  |work=O Globo|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=30 May 2019|author=Gabriel Martins}}</ref><ref name=\"book\" /> and was followed by the slowest recovery.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== Context ==\n=== Economic ===\nBrazil's economy is largely dependent on the export of [[commodities]], particularly iron ore, petroleum and soy. From the late 1990s till 2012, prices for these export commodities rose significantly (partly because of increasing demand from [[China]]), resulting in about two decades of economic growth. As a result of the economic crisis, Brazil's GDP dropped sharply, leading to high unemployment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|date=2016-05-01|website=Ag\u00eancia Brasil|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> During [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]]'s left-wing presidency from 2003 to 2010, the government redistributed wealth through welfare programs and raised the [[minimum wage]] in order to increase consumption.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|title=Entenda a crise econ\u00f4mica|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/entenda-crise-economica|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |date=15 May 2016 |author=Giselle Garcia |agency=[[Ag\u00eancia Brasil]]}}</ref>\n\nIn response to critics of Lula's [[Socialist economics|socialist economic]] stance, his successor, Dilma Rousseff (president during the crisis), introduced [[Macroeconomics|macroeconomic]] tax exemptions and subsidies. These policies are widely acknowledged as a major factor in the 2014\u201316 economic crisis.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n=== Political ===\nThe economic crisis was followed and intensified by a political crisis. In 2014, a series of corruption scandals uncovered by [[Operation Car Wash]] engulfed many influential politicians. In the presidential election of the same year, President [[Dilma Rousseff]] was re-elected to a second term, defeating the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PSDB]] candidate [[A\u00e9cio Neves]] by a narrow margin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Na disputa mais acirrada da hist\u00f3ria, Dilma \u00e9 reeleita presidente do Brasil - 26/10/2014 - Poder|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2014/10/1537894-dilma-e-reeleita-presidente-do-brasil.shtml|work=Folha de S.Paulo|accessdate=2019-06-09}}</ref> The result was not recognized by a section of the opposition and provoked popular discontent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crise econ\u00f4mica e corrup\u00e7\u00e3o marcar\u00e3o a nova presid\u00eancia|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2014/10/26/politica/1414356634_215134.html|work=EL PA\u00cdS|date=2014-10-27|accessdate=2019-06-09|first=Antonio Jim\u00e9nez|last=Barca}}</ref> Due to the disputed legitimacy of the election, the Operation Car Wash investigation, and the economic crisis, dissatisfaction with the government became widespread. By 2015, Rousseff's approval rating had plummeted to 8% according to a [[Datafolha]] survey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/08/17/brazils-corruption-scandal-economy-drive-rousseffs-ratings-to-record-low/|title=Brazil\u2019s corruption scandal, economy drive Rousseff\u2019s ratings to record low|last=NW|first=1615 L. St|last2=Suite 800Washington|website=Pew Research Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31|last3=Inquiries|first3=DC 20036USA202-419-4300 {{!}} Main202-857-8562 {{!}} Fax202-419-4372 {{!}} Media}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://media.folha.uol.com.br/datafolha/2015/08/06/avaliacao_dilma_agosto_2015.pdf|title=Avalia\u00e7\u00e3do DO Governo Dilma Rousseff|publisher=Datafolha Instituto|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Causes ==\n===Slowdown of the Chinese economy and fall in commodity prices===\nAccording to Steve Tobin, a researcher at the [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO), decreased external [[demand]] for Brazilian products, particularly from China, plus the fall in commodity prices, contributed to the crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|date=2016-05-01|website=Ag\u00eancia Brasil|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Silvia Matos, a researcher at the Brazilian think-tank and university [[Get\u00falio Vargas Foundation]], concluded that external factors were responsible for 30% of the crisis.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MjY8DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Crise de Crescimento do Brasil|author=FGV|publisher=Elsevier Brasil|language=pt-BR|isbn=9788535266382|date=2016-05-05}}</ref> During the downturn, the Brazilian economy exhibited structural weaknesses that had never been seen before, such as low [[productivity]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil}}</ref>\n=== Macroeconomic policy errors ===\n[[Image:Entrevistas_Diversas_(14879045080).jpg|thumb|[[Guido Mantega]], Finance Minister, during the first Dilma administration. In July 2012, he admitted for the first time that the government had put into practice a new \"macroeconomic matrix\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Mantega indica novo modelo econ\u00f4mico|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,mantega-indica-novo-modelo-economico-imp-,896017|work=Estad\u00e3o|location=Bras\u00edlia|author=Beatriz Abreu|date=5 July 2012|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nAlthough decreasing prices for Brazil's exports contributed to the economic crisis, there is a consensus that the primary cause was internal. [[Gustavo Franco]], former president of the [[Central Bank of Brazil]], has asserted that the crisis was entirely self-inflicted by a series of \"local macroeconomic measures that went wrong.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=A crise brasileira n\u00e3o vem de fora, ela foi autoinfligida|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2015/03/25/economia/1427322429_883162.html|work=El Pa\u00eds |date=27 March 2015}}</ref> These measures are collectively known as the ''{{ill|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|pt|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|vertical-align=sup}}'' (\"New Economic Matrix\"). \n\nPreviously, the government had played a major role in the expansion of the internal market by stimulating consumption, raising the national minimum wage, transferring wealth and expanding credit. By the end of Lula's administration, entrepreneurs and industrialists began to question the sustainability of these policies. They complained about the national industry's declining share of Brazilian GDP.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nIn response to these concerns, Rousseff created the New Economic Matrix in an attempt to help the Brazilian industry become more competitive internationally. These measures included tax exemptions and subsidies which ultimately failed to stimulate industry. Productivity, after growing by 2.7% in 2010, fell by 0.9% and 3.7% in the following two years, shrinking government revenues and thus requiring reductions in public investment.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n=== Political instability ===\nIn the same year the crisis began, a major corruption scheme involving top politicians and major companies such as the oil giant [[Petrobras]] was uncovered by [[Operation Car Wash]]. It is estimated that Operation Car Wash caused Brazil's GDP to contract by 1 to 1.5%.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2017-06-02|title=A Lava Jato est\u00e1 corroendo o PIB. E da\u00ed?|url=https://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/lava-jato-esta-corroendo-o-pib-e-dai/|journal=Isto \u00c9 Dinheiro|publisher=Editora tr\u00eas}}</ref>\n\n== Consequences ==\n=== Unemployment ===\n[[File:Evolu\u00e7\u00e3o do desemprego 2012-2017.png|thumb|355px|The unemployment rate from 2012 to 2017. Each vertical line corresponds to a month.<ref name=\"desemprego\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106064226/https://br.advfn.com/indicadores/pnad|title=Desemprego {{!}} Pnad {{!}} IBGE|date=2017-11-06|accessdate=2017-11-26}}</ref>]]\nBefore the recession, Brazil's [[unemployment]] rate hovered around 6.8% for most of 2014, but began increasing in February 2015, resulting in a 2015 average of 8.5%. The economy lost more than 1.5 million jobs throughout 2015, fueling public discontent against the political establishment and the political leadership of the [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Worker's Party]] and President [[Dilma Rousseff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-15/brazil-s-unemployment-jumps-in-2015-adding-to-rousseff-s-woes|title=Brazil's unemployment jumps in 2015, adding to Rousseff's woes|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> The unemployment rate continued to rise throughout 2016 to finish the year at 12.0%, with 12.3 million people unemployed and an estimated 2.8 million private-sector jobs cut over the preceding two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-economy-employment-idUSKBN15F1LE|title=Brazil's jobless rate ends 2016 at 12 percent with 12.3 million unemployed|publisher=Reuters|date=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nYoung people were affected most by the worsening job market. While the overall unemployment rate was 12.7% in the first trimester of 2019, the rate in people from 14 to 17 years was 44.5% and 27.3% for people from 18 to 24 years. \n\nExperts expressed concern for the unintended economic and social repercussions for Brazil's younger population, as the economic crisis decreased social security contributions and depreciated [[human capital]] (caused by the decrease in the technical capacity of future workers).<ref>{{cite web |title=Desemprego deixa heran\u00e7a maldita aos jovens e cicatrizes no pa\u00eds |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/economia/desemprego-deixa-heranca-maldita-aos-jovens-e-cicatrizes-no-pais/ |work=Exame|date=28 June 2019|author=Ligia Tuon|accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Recession ===\n[[File:Crescimento do PIB do Brasil entre 2010 e 2016.png|355px|thumb|Change in GDP from 2010 to 2016 in Brazil.<ref name=\"oglobo\">{{cite web|title=Economia encolhe 3,6% em 2016 e pa\u00eds tem pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/economia-encolhe-36-em-2016-pais-tem-pior-recessao-da-historia-21022917|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Growth slowed significantly in 2014 which was followed by two consecutive drops.<br /><br />(Note: The values for 2015 and 2016 were later revised to 3,5% and 3,3%, respectively.)]]\n\nAt the end of the second trimester of 2014, the country was in a technical recession. According to some Brazilian economists, a technical recession is negative economic growth for two consecutive quarters. It is different from an actual recession, in which the situation of the country depreciates significantly.<ref>{{cite web |title=Entenda o que a recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica significa para a economia|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,entenda-o-que-a-recessao-tecnica-significa-para-a-economia,384664|work=Estad\u00e3o|author=Alessandra Corr\u00eaa|date=9 June 2009}}</ref> Finance Minister, [[Guido Mantega]], lessened the economic result and, in comparison to Europe, declared that:\n\n{{quote|[In Brazil] we're talking about two trimesters [of negative GDP growth], and we know that the economy is in motion. Recession is when there are rising unemployment and decreasing income. Here we have the opposite.|Guido Mantega, Finance Minister<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2014/08/entenda-o-que-e-recessao-tecnica.html|work=G1|date=29 August 2014|accessdate=7 December 2016|title=Entenda o que \u00e9 recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica|location=S\u00e3o Paulo}}</ref>|title=|source=}}\n\nRegardless of Mantega's statements, specialists had already spotted signs that a strong recession was well underway, citing the technical recession and later, the small growth of 0.5% at the end of 2014. The expectations were confirmed in the next year when the economy shrunk by 3.5%. In 2016, there was another sharp decrease of 3.3%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou (e pode sair) da maior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://exame.abril.com.br/economia/como-o-brasil-entrou-e-pode-sair-da-maior-recessao-da-historia/|accessdate=24 June 2017|work=EXAME|date=7 March 2017|author=Jo\u00e3o Pedro Caleiro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou, sozinho, na pior crise da hist\u00f3ria|work=\u00c9poca|accessdate= 24 June 2017|author1=Graziele Oliveira |author2=Marcos Coronato|url=http://epoca.globo.com/ideias/noticia/2016/04/como-o-brasil-entrou-sozinho-na-pior-crise-da-historia.html|date=4 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=3 July 2017|title=Brasil vive a pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-hoje/noticia/2017/03/brasil-vive-pior-recessao-da-historia.html|accessdate=2017-06-01|work = Jornal Hoje|author1=Renata Capucci |author2=Larissa Castro}}</ref> In the first trimester of 2017, the GDP rose for the first time after eight consecutive trimesters of negative growth.<ref name=\"jn\">{{cite journal|date=2017-06-01|title=PIB do primeiro trimestre cresce 1% ap\u00f3s oito quedas seguidas|language=pt|trans-title=First quarter GDP grows 1% after eight straight falls|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-nacional/noticia/2017/06/pib-do-primeiro-trimestre-cresce-1-apos-oito-quedas-seguidas.html|journal=Jornal Nacional|accessdate= 24 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe recession caused a [[fiscal crisis]] and an increasing [[budget deficit]] which, according to Bloomberg, was \"the largest-ever primary budget gap ... as a two-year [[economic recession]] sapped tax collection while expenses grew further.\"<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-30/brazil-posts-largest-budget-deficit-for-february-ever\n|title=Brazil posts largest budget deficit for February ever\n|publisher=Bloomberg\n|accessdate=18 May 2016\n}}\n</ref> The government deficit reached 5.8 billion [[Brazilian real|reais]] (US$1.7 billion) in the first three months of 2016, the widest reported since December 2001. The two-year fiscal deterioration can be explained by the decrease in government revenue from taxes as a result of the recession, while government expenses have been growing constantly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-29/brazil-records-worst-ever-first-quarter-budget-deficit|title=Brazil records worst-ever first quarter budget deficit|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Increase in economic inequality ===\n[[File:Gini da Renda do Trabalho nos Domic\u00edlios per Capita.png|355px|thumb|Evolution of the [[Gini coefficient]] in Brazil from 2012 to 2019. Source:Ibre/FGV<ref name=\"IBRE\" />]]\nA 2019 study by the [[Instituto Brasileiro de Economia]] (Ibre), part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]] (FGV), obtained by the magazine [[Valor Econ\u00f4mico]], showed that the [[Gini coefficient]], which measures the economic inequality in society from 0 to 1, had increased year after year since 2015 and reached its peak in March 2019.\n\nIn 7 years, the accumulated wealth of the top 10% rose by 8.5%, while that of the 40% poorest dropped 14%. The research showed that people with lower incomes suffered the effects of the crisis more intensely and recovered from the crisis slower. <ref>{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil atinge o maior patamar j\u00e1 registrado, diz FGV/IBRE|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2019/05/21/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-atinge-o-maior-patamar-ja-registrado-diz-fgvibre.ghtml|work=G1|accessdate=2019-05-22|date=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Valor\">{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil sobe pelo 17\u00ba trimestre consecutivo|url=https://www.valor.com.br/brasil/6265917/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-sobe-pelo-17-trimestre-consecutivo|work=Valor Econ\u00f4mico|date=2019-05-19|accessdate=2019-05-22|author=Bruno Villas B\u00f4as|location=Rio de Janeiro}}</ref><ref name=\"IBRE\">{{cite web |title=Levantamento do FGV IBRE aponta desigualdade recorde na renda do trabalho |url=https://portalibre.fgv.br/navegacao-superior/noticias/levantamento-do-fgv-ibre-aponta-desigualdade-recorde-na-renda-do-trabalho.htm |work=IBRE/FGV |accessdate=23 May 2019 |date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an Ibre researcher, Daniel Duque, the recovery of the job market benefited the  higher qualified and experienced most, reinforcing inequality. Many underqualified people gave up trying to get a job, and the loss of hope was at a \"[...] record high, and it helps to explain why, even after the decrease in unemployment, inequality kept rising.\"<ref name=\"Valor\" />\n\n=== Emigration ===\n{{main article|Brazilian diaspora}}\n[[File:Quantidade de declara\u00e7\u00f5es de sa\u00edda definitiva do Brasil.jpg|thumb|355px|Number of declarations of definite emigration from the country. Source:[[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=Cresce n\u00famero de brasileiros que decidem viver no exterior; pa\u00edses oferecem oportunidades de emprego|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/concursos-e-emprego/noticia/2019/04/03/cresce-numero-de-brasileiros-que-decidem-viver-no-exterior-paises-oferecem-oportunidades-de-emprego.ghtml|work=G1|author=Luiz Guilherme Gerbelli|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=3 April 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nThe number of declarations of definitive departure from the country began to grow in the first year of crisis and has increased steadily ever since, according to [[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]]. Among the countries that received the most Brazilian citizens were [[Japan]] and [[Canada]], which, due to low unemployment and aging populations among other reasons, needed a boost to decrease the age of the workforce.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAccording to a JBJ Partners employee (a company specialized in expatriation to the [[United States]]), many who fled Brazil were qualified workers:\n\n{{quote|We're talking about qualified people. The profile of the immigrant is no longer that of the poor individual looking for better opportunities. They are high executives, who are abandoning their careers to open a business abroad, people with Ph.D., which is sad because the country is losing resources.|Jorge Botrel, a JBJ partner.<ref>{{cite web |title=Com a crise, dispara a quantidade de brasileiros que desistem de viver no Brasil |url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/com-a-crise-dispara-a-quantidade-de-brasileiros-que-desistem-de-viver-no-brasil.ghtml |work=G1|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=17 December 2017|author=Lu\u00edsa Melo}}</ref>}}\n\nAn [[OECD]] report shows an even higher number<!-- In comparison to what? -->. In 2016 80,000 Brazilians emigrated legally to one of the member states of the OECD, whereas 99,000 did so in 2017. Similarly, data from Receita Federal shows that the number of people leaving Brazil increased in consecutive years since the beginning of the crisis.<ref>{{cite web |title=Imigra\u00e7\u00e3o de brasileiros para pa\u00edses da OCDE subiu 24%, o terceiro maior aumento |url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2019/09/18/politica/1568843366_553673.html |work=El Pa\u00eds|author=Felipe Betim|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Credit rating ===\nThis is a table of the credit ratings of the Brazilian economy according to Trading Economics.{{who|date=April 2017}}{{cn|date=April 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Agency !! Rating !! Outlook !! Date\n|-\n| Fitch || BB || negative || May 5, 2016\n|-\n| TE || 34 || negative || Apr 16 2016\n|-\n| Moody's || Ba2 || negative || Feb 24 2016\n|-\n| S&P || BB || negative || Feb 17 2016\n|}\n\n== Anti-crisis measures ==\n[[File:Entrevistas Diversas (30847431200).jpg|[[Henrique Meirelles]], the [[Ministry of Finance (Brazil)|Minister of Finance]] from May 2016 to April 2018.|thumb]]\nSince the impeachment of Dilma Rousseff and [[Michel Temer]]'s subsequent rise to power, several measures, most of which unpopular, were implemented or proposed to get the economy back on track.<ref>{{cite journal|title='Aproveito impopularidade para tomar medidas necess\u00e1rias', diz Temer|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2016/12/1843702-aproveito-impopularidade-para-tomar-medidas-necessarias-diz-temer.shtml|journal=Folha de S.Paulo|date=22 December 2016|accessdate=17 June 2017|author=Marina Dias Valdo Cruz|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref> The most important of which were:\n\n* The {{ill|95\u00ba Constitutional amendment|pt|Emenda Constitucional do Teto dos Gastos P\u00fablicos|vertical-align=sup}} (a.k.a \"new fiscal regime\"): Constitutional amendment which established a \"ceiling\" (upper limit) to government spending for the next 20 years;<ref>{{cite journal|title=Temer elogia aprova\u00e7\u00e3o da PEC do Teto e minimiza menor n\u00famero de votos a favor|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2016-12/temer-elogia-aprovacao-da-pec-do-teto-e-minimiza-menor-numero-de-votos|accessdate=17 June 2017|location=Bras\u00edlia|journal= Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=13 December 2016|author=Paulo Victor Chagas}}</ref>\n* The [[Outsourcing law in Brazil|Outsourcing law]], which allows companies to hire outsourced employees to work on primary activities, and not just secondary activities (such as security or cleaning);<ref>{{cite web|title=Com vetos, Temer sanciona lei que permite terceiriza\u00e7\u00e3o de atividade-fim|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-03/temer-sanciona-lei-que-permite-terceirizacao-em-atividade-fim-das-empresas|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=31 March 2017|author=Ivan Richard Esposito|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref>\n* The [[Brazil labor reform (2017)|2017 labor reform]], a significant change in the [[Consolidation of Labor Laws]]; and<ref>{{cite web|title=Com flexibiliza\u00e7\u00e3o de v\u00e1rios pontos da CLT, reforma trabalhista divide opini\u00f5es|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-04/com-flexibilizacao-de-varios-pontos-da-clt-reforma-trabalhista-divide|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|location=S\u00e3o Paulo|date=13 April 2017|author=Daniel Mello}}</ref>\n* a pension reform, which the government failed to approve.<ref>{{cite web|title=Governo desiste da vota\u00e7\u00e3o da Previd\u00eancia e anuncia nova pauta priorit\u00e1ria no Congresso|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/governo-desiste-da-votacao-da-previdencia-e-anuncia-nova-pauta-prioritaria-no-congresso.ghtml||work = G1|accessdate=26 May 2019|date=19 February 2018|author1=Guilherme Mazui |author2=Roniara Castilhos}}</ref>\n\nOne year after the labor reform was approved, however, it was verified that the decrease in unemployment was minimal, while the contracts of intermittent, outsourced and temporary labor increased.<ref>{{cite web|author=Fabiana Futema|date=10 November 2018|title=Um ano depois, reforma trabalhista n\u00e3o gera empregos esperados|url=https://veja.abril.com.br/economia/um-ano-depois-reforma-trabalhista-nao-gera-empregos-esperados/|work=VEJA.com|accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Recovery ==\nIn early 2017, there were already signals that the economy was beginning to recover, however, it was agreed that the process would be long and slow.<ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ser\u00e1 longa e lenta, aponta 'FT'|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-sera-longa-e-lenta-aponta-ft,70001658076}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ainda \u00e9 lenta, diz presidente do Ita\u00fa|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/mercado/2017/04/1876544-recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-ainda-e-lenta-diz-presidente-do-itau.shtml}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, a 1% rise in GDP in the first quarter of the year was reported.<ref name=\"jn\"/> It was the first rise of the GDP after eight consecutive falls (two years).<ref name=\":0\">\n{{Cite news|title= PIB do Brasil cresce 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre de 2017, ap\u00f3s 8 quedas seguidas|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-do-brasil-cresce-10-no-1-trimestre-de-2017.ghtml}}</ref> Minister of Finance [[Henrique Meirelles]] said that the country had left the \"greatest recession of the century.\"<ref>{{citation |title=PIB sobe 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre, ap\u00f3s oito quedas consecutivas|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,pib-sobe-1-0-no-1-trimestre-apos-oito-quedas-consecutivas,70001821658}}</ref> However, economists say that the growth characterizes only the end of the \"technical recession\" and that it is still too early to claim that the crisis is over, given that unemployment remains high and there's still widespread uncertainty regarding the future of the economy, especially in the aftermath of the recent political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Comparisons with other crises ==\n[[Image:Countries_by_Real_GDP_Growth_Rate_(2016).svg|thumb|Real GDP growth in 2016. Source:''CIA World Factbook''<ref>{{cite web|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2003rank.html|work=Central Intelligence Agency (CIA)}}</ref>|355px]]\nIn countries with similar size and wealth, there were a few, but less severe crisis in the same period. In 2015, among [[OECD]] countries, only [[Russia]] went through a recession. Even after the economic sanctions imposed by other countries due to the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|conflict in Ukraine]], Russia's GDP fell by only 4% in two years (2015 and 2016). Few other countries in this period were going through a recession, which reinforces the argument that the crisis in Brazil was mainly due to local causes.<ref name=\"book\">{{Cite book|last=Carvalho|first=Laura|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XppWDwAAQBAJ|title=Valsa brasileira: Do boom ao caos econ\u00f4mico|date=2018-05-08|publisher=Editora Todavia S.A|isbn=978-85-93828-63-8|language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n\nIn comparison to other crises in Brazil, it was verified that the 2014 crisis was not the deepest, as previously thought. After the GDP values for 2015 and 2016 were reviewed by the [[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics]] (IBGE), the economy shrank by 8.2% in the period, in contrast to the 8.5% in the 1981 recession. Despite not being the deepest, the crisis was long. It was also followed by the slowest recovery of all.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nAccording to Codace (committee part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]]), the 1981 crisis lasted nine trimesters, reached its peak in the first trimester of 1983 and, since then, took seven trimesters for the GDP the reach its pre-crisis level. Later, the 1989-1992 crisis lasted 11 trimesters and the recovery time was the same: seven trimesters. This crisis, however, had a lower intensity, with an accumulated decrease in the GDP of 7.7%.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nIn turn, the GDP after the 2014 crisis will only reach its pre-crisis level in 2022, according to an optimistic estimate, with 20 trimesters of recovery in total. When taking into account not only the GDP, but also the employment rate, the recovery will be even slower. In addition to the sluggish recovery, the new jobs will be of lower quality, including informal and autonomous labor.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Brazil labor reform (2017)]]\n* [[Economy of Brazil]]\n* [[2018 in Brazil]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Government of Michel Temer}}\n{{Financial crises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2014 Brazilian economic recession}}\n[[Category:2010s economic history]]\n[[Category:2014 in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Economic crises in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Recessions]]\n[[Category:Government of Michel Temer]]\n[[Category:Economic history of Brazil]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Crisis that began during the presidency of Dilma Rousseff}}\n{{Copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Brazil's fall (The Economist).jpg|thumb|January 2016 cover of ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine about the crisis. The cover depicts then-president Dilma Rousseff.]]\n\nFrom mid-2014 onward, [[Brazil]] experienced a severe [[financial crisis#Wider economic crisis|economic crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/michel-temer-signs-security-decree-stem-rio-violence-180216183747559.html|title=Michel Temer signs security decree to stem Rio violence|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Barua |first1=Akrur |title=Brazil: Yearning for the good times |url=http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |series=Global Economic Outlook, Q2 2016 |publisher=Deloitte University Press |accessdate=21 May 2016 |date=29 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823114946/http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |archive-date=23 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The country's [[gross domestic product|Gross Domestic Product]] (GDP) fell by 3.5% in 2015 and 3.3% in 2016, after which an economic recovery began.\n\nThe economic crisis occurred alongside a political crisis that resulted in the impeachment of former president [[Dilma Rousseff]]. Together these events caused mass popular dissatisfaction with the political system. In the first quarter of 2017, Brazil's GDP rose by 1%. This was the first GDP increase to occur in eight consecutive quarters. Finance Minister [[Henrique Meirelles]] announced that Brazil had \"emerged from the greatest crisis of the century\". <ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-03/08/c_136110450.htm |title=Brazil GDP falls by 3.6 percent in 2016 |author=Mu Xuequan |date=March 8, 2017}}</ref> However, the rise in GDP marked only the end of a technical recession, not the end of the crisis.\n\nDuring the economic crisis, high unemployment rates were reported throughout the country, and there was widespread uncertainty regarding Brazil's economic future following a series of political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|date=2017-06-01|author=Darlan Alvarenga|accessdate=5 June 2017|work=G1}}</ref> The [[recession]] was the second most severe in the country's [[economic history of Brazil|history]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,com-revisao-ultima-recessao-deixa-de-ser-a-maior-da-historia,70002628638|title=Com revis\u00e3o, \u00faltima recess\u00e3o deixa de ser a maior da hist\u00f3ria |work=Estad\u00e3o|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=1 December 2018|author=Vinicius Neder}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/estagnacao-recessao-ou-depressao-pib-confirma-retomada-mais-fraca-das-ultimas-decadas-23704758|title=Estagna\u00e7\u00e3o, recess\u00e3o ou depress\u00e3o? PIB confirma retomada mais fraca das \u00faltimas d\u00e9cadas  |work=O Globo|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=30 May 2019|author=Gabriel Martins}}</ref><ref name=\"book\" /> and was followed by the slowest recovery.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== Context ==\n=== Economic ===\nBrazil's economy is largely dependent on the export of [[commodities]], particularly iron ore, petroleum and soy. From the late 1990s till 2012, prices for these export commodities rose significantly (partly because of increasing demand from [[China]]), resulting in about two decades of economic growth. As a result of the economic crisis, Brazil's GDP dropped sharply, leading to high unemployment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|date=2016-05-01|website=Ag\u00eancia Brasil|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> During [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]]'s left-wing presidency from 2003 to 2010, the government redistributed wealth through welfare programs and raised the [[minimum wage]] in order to increase consumption.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|title=Entenda a crise econ\u00f4mica|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/entenda-crise-economica|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |date=15 May 2016 |author=Giselle Garcia |agency=[[Ag\u00eancia Brasil]]}}</ref>\n\nIn response to critics of Lula's [[Socialist economics|socialist economic]] stance, his successor, Dilma Rousseff (president during the crisis), introduced [[Macroeconomics|macroeconomic]] tax exemptions and subsidies. These policies are widely acknowledged as a major factor in the 2014\u201316 economic crisis.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n=== Political ===\nThe economic crisis was followed and intensified by a political crisis. In 2014, a series of corruption scandals uncovered by [[Operation Car Wash]] engulfed many influential politicians. In the presidential election of the same year, President [[Dilma Rousseff]] was re-elected to a second term, defeating the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PSDB]] candidate [[A\u00e9cio Neves]] by a narrow margin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Na disputa mais acirrada da hist\u00f3ria, Dilma \u00e9 reeleita presidente do Brasil - 26/10/2014 - Poder|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2014/10/1537894-dilma-e-reeleita-presidente-do-brasil.shtml|work=Folha de S.Paulo|accessdate=2019-06-09}}</ref> The result was not recognized by a section of the opposition and provoked popular discontent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crise econ\u00f4mica e corrup\u00e7\u00e3o marcar\u00e3o a nova presid\u00eancia|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2014/10/26/politica/1414356634_215134.html|work=EL PA\u00cdS|date=2014-10-27|accessdate=2019-06-09|first=Antonio Jim\u00e9nez|last=Barca}}</ref> Due to the disputed legitimacy of the election, the Operation Car Wash investigation, and the economic crisis, dissatisfaction with the government became widespread. By 2015, Rousseff's approval rating had plummeted to 8% according to a [[Datafolha]] survey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/08/17/brazils-corruption-scandal-economy-drive-rousseffs-ratings-to-record-low/|title=Brazil\u2019s corruption scandal, economy drive Rousseff\u2019s ratings to record low|last=NW|first=1615 L. St|last2=Suite 800Washington|website=Pew Research Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31|last3=Inquiries|first3=DC 20036USA202-419-4300 {{!}} Main202-857-8562 {{!}} Fax202-419-4372 {{!}} Media}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://media.folha.uol.com.br/datafolha/2015/08/06/avaliacao_dilma_agosto_2015.pdf|title=Avalia\u00e7\u00e3do DO Governo Dilma Rousseff|publisher=Datafolha Instituto|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Causes ==\n===Slowdown of the Chinese economy and fall in commodity prices===\nAccording to Steve Tobin, a researcher at the [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO), decreased external [[demand]] for Brazilian products, particularly from China, plus the fall in commodity prices, contributed to the crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|date=2016-05-01|website=Ag\u00eancia Brasil|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Silvia Matos, a researcher at the Brazilian think-tank and university [[Get\u00falio Vargas Foundation]], concluded that external factors were responsible for 30% of the crisis.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MjY8DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Crise de Crescimento do Brasil|author=FGV|publisher=Elsevier Brasil|language=pt-BR|isbn=9788535266382|date=2016-05-05}}</ref> During the downturn, the Brazilian economy exhibited structural weaknesses that had never been seen before, such as low [[productivity]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil}}</ref>\n=== Macroeconomic policy errors ===\n[[Image:Entrevistas_Diversas_(14879045080).jpg|thumb|[[Guido Mantega]], Finance Minister, during the first Dilma administration. In July 2012, he admitted for the first time that the government had put into practice a new \"macroeconomic matrix\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Mantega indica novo modelo econ\u00f4mico|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,mantega-indica-novo-modelo-economico-imp-,896017|work=Estad\u00e3o|location=Bras\u00edlia|author=Beatriz Abreu|date=5 July 2012|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nAlthough decreasing prices for Brazil's exports contributed to the economic crisis, there is a consensus that the primary cause was internal. [[Gustavo Franco]], former president of the [[Central Bank of Brazil]], has asserted that the crisis was entirely self-inflicted by a series of \"local macroeconomic measures that went wrong.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=A crise brasileira n\u00e3o vem de fora, ela foi autoinfligida|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2015/03/25/economia/1427322429_883162.html|work=El Pa\u00eds |date=27 March 2015}}</ref> These measures are collectively known as the ''{{ill|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|pt|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|vertical-align=sup}}'' (\"New Economic Matrix\"). \n\nPreviously, the government had played a major role in the expansion of the internal market by stimulating consumption, raising the national minimum wage, transferring wealth and expanding credit. By the end of Lula's administration, entrepreneurs and industrialists began to question the sustainability of these policies. They complained about the national industry's declining share of Brazilian GDP.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nIn response to these concerns, Rousseff created the New Economic Matrix in an attempt to help the Brazilian industry become more competitive internationally. These measures included tax exemptions and subsidies which ultimately failed to stimulate industry. Productivity, after growing by 2.7% in 2010, fell by 0.9% and 3.7% in the following two years, shrinking government revenues and thus requiring reductions in public investment.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n=== Political instability ===\nIn the same year the crisis began, a major corruption scheme involving top politicians and major companies such as the oil giant [[Petrobras]] was uncovered by [[Operation Car Wash]]. It is estimated that Operation Car Wash caused Brazil's GDP to contract by 1 to 1.5%.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2017-06-02|title=A Lava Jato est\u00e1 corroendo o PIB. E da\u00ed?|url=https://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/lava-jato-esta-corroendo-o-pib-e-dai/|journal=Isto \u00c9 Dinheiro|publisher=Editora tr\u00eas}}</ref>\n\n== Consequences ==\n=== Unemployment ===\n[[File:Evolu\u00e7\u00e3o do desemprego 2012-2017.png|thumb|355px|The unemployment rate from 2012 to 2017. Each vertical line corresponds to a month.<ref name=\"desemprego\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106064226/https://br.advfn.com/indicadores/pnad|title=Desemprego {{!}} Pnad {{!}} IBGE|date=2017-11-06|accessdate=2017-11-26}}</ref>]]\nBefore the recession, Brazil's [[unemployment]] rate hovered around 6.8% for most of 2014, but began increasing in February 2015, resulting in a 2015 average of 8.5%. The economy lost more than 1.5 million jobs throughout 2015, fueling public discontent against the political establishment and the political leadership of the [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Worker's Party]] and President [[Dilma Rousseff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-15/brazil-s-unemployment-jumps-in-2015-adding-to-rousseff-s-woes|title=Brazil's unemployment jumps in 2015, adding to Rousseff's woes|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> The unemployment rate continued to rise throughout 2016 to finish the year at 12.0%, with 12.3 million people unemployed and an estimated 2.8 million private-sector jobs cut over the preceding two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-economy-employment-idUSKBN15F1LE|title=Brazil's jobless rate ends 2016 at 12 percent with 12.3 million unemployed|publisher=Reuters|date=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nYoung people were affected most by the worsening job market. While the overall unemployment rate was 12.7% in the first trimester of 2019, the rate in people from 14 to 17 years was 44.5% and 27.3% for people from 18 to 24 years. \n\nExperts expressed concern for the unintended economic and social repercussions for Brazil's younger population, as the economic crisis decreased social security contributions and depreciated [[human capital]] (caused by the decrease in the technical capacity of future workers).<ref>{{cite web |title=Desemprego deixa heran\u00e7a maldita aos jovens e cicatrizes no pa\u00eds |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/economia/desemprego-deixa-heranca-maldita-aos-jovens-e-cicatrizes-no-pais/ |work=Exame|date=28 June 2019|author=Ligia Tuon|accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Recession ===\n[[File:Crescimento do PIB do Brasil entre 2010 e 2016.png|355px|thumb|Change in GDP from 2010 to 2016 in Brazil.<ref name=\"oglobo\">{{cite web|title=Economia encolhe 3,6% em 2016 e pa\u00eds tem pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/economia-encolhe-36-em-2016-pais-tem-pior-recessao-da-historia-21022917|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Growth slowed significantly in 2014 which was followed by two consecutive drops.<br /><br />(Note: The values for 2015 and 2016 were later revised to 3,5% and 3,3%, respectively.)]]\n\nAt the end of the second trimester of 2014, the country was in a technical recession. According to some Brazilian economists, a technical recession is negative economic growth for two consecutive quarters. It is different from an actual recession, in which the situation of the country depreciates significantly.<ref>{{cite web |title=Entenda o que a recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica significa para a economia|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,entenda-o-que-a-recessao-tecnica-significa-para-a-economia,384664|work=Estad\u00e3o|author=Alessandra Corr\u00eaa|date=9 June 2009}}</ref> Finance Minister, [[Guido Mantega]], lessened the economic result and, in comparison to Europe, declared that:\n\n{{quote|[In Brazil] we're talking about two trimesters [of negative GDP growth], and we know that the economy is in motion. Recession is when there are rising unemployment and decreasing income. Here we have the opposite.|Guido Mantega, Finance Minister<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2014/08/entenda-o-que-e-recessao-tecnica.html|work=G1|date=29 August 2014|accessdate=7 December 2016|title=Entenda o que \u00e9 recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica|location=S\u00e3o Paulo}}</ref>|title=|source=}}\n\nRegardless of Mantega's statements, specialists had already spotted signs that a strong recession was well underway, citing the technical recession and later, the small growth of 0.5% at the end of 2014. The expectations were confirmed in the next year when the economy shrunk by 3.5%. In 2016, there was another sharp decrease of 3.3%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou (e pode sair) da maior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://exame.abril.com.br/economia/como-o-brasil-entrou-e-pode-sair-da-maior-recessao-da-historia/|accessdate=24 June 2017|work=EXAME|date=7 March 2017|author=Jo\u00e3o Pedro Caleiro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou, sozinho, na pior crise da hist\u00f3ria|work=\u00c9poca|accessdate= 24 June 2017|author1=Graziele Oliveira |author2=Marcos Coronato|url=http://epoca.globo.com/ideias/noticia/2016/04/como-o-brasil-entrou-sozinho-na-pior-crise-da-historia.html|date=4 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=3 July 2017|title=Brasil vive a pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-hoje/noticia/2017/03/brasil-vive-pior-recessao-da-historia.html|accessdate=2017-06-01|work = Jornal Hoje|author1=Renata Capucci |author2=Larissa Castro}}</ref> In the first trimester of 2017, the GDP rose for the first time after eight consecutive trimesters of negative growth.<ref name=\"jn\">{{cite journal|date=2017-06-01|title=PIB do primeiro trimestre cresce 1% ap\u00f3s oito quedas seguidas|language=pt|trans-title=First quarter GDP grows 1% after eight straight falls|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-nacional/noticia/2017/06/pib-do-primeiro-trimestre-cresce-1-apos-oito-quedas-seguidas.html|journal=Jornal Nacional|accessdate= 24 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe recession caused a [[fiscal crisis]] and an increasing [[budget deficit]] which, according to Bloomberg, was \"the largest-ever primary budget gap ... as a two-year [[economic recession]] sapped tax collection while expenses grew further.\"<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-30/brazil-posts-largest-budget-deficit-for-february-ever\n|title=Brazil posts largest budget deficit for February ever\n|publisher=Bloomberg\n|accessdate=18 May 2016\n}}\n</ref> The government deficit reached 5.8 billion [[Brazilian real|reais]] (US$1.7 billion) in the first three months of 2016, the widest reported since December 2001. The two-year fiscal deterioration can be explained by the decrease in government revenue from taxes as a result of the recession, while government expenses have been growing constantly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-29/brazil-records-worst-ever-first-quarter-budget-deficit|title=Brazil records worst-ever first quarter budget deficit|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Increase in economic inequality ===\n[[File:Gini da Renda do Trabalho nos Domic\u00edlios per Capita.png|355px|thumb|Evolution of the [[Gini coefficient]] in Brazil from 2012 to 2019. Source:Ibre/FGV<ref name=\"IBRE\" />]]\nA 2019 study by the [[Instituto Brasileiro de Economia]] (Ibre), part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]] (FGV), obtained by the magazine [[Valor Econ\u00f4mico]], showed that the [[Gini coefficient]], which measures the economic inequality in society from 0 to 1, had increased year after year since 2015 and reached its peak in March 2019.\n\nIn 7 years, the accumulated wealth of the top 10% rose by 8.5%, while that of the 40% poorest dropped 14%. The research showed that people with lower incomes suffered the effects of the crisis more intensely and recovered from the crisis slower. <ref>{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil atinge o maior patamar j\u00e1 registrado, diz FGV/IBRE|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2019/05/21/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-atinge-o-maior-patamar-ja-registrado-diz-fgvibre.ghtml|work=G1|accessdate=2019-05-22|date=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Valor\">{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil sobe pelo 17\u00ba trimestre consecutivo|url=https://www.valor.com.br/brasil/6265917/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-sobe-pelo-17-trimestre-consecutivo|work=Valor Econ\u00f4mico|date=2019-05-19|accessdate=2019-05-22|author=Bruno Villas B\u00f4as|location=Rio de Janeiro}}</ref><ref name=\"IBRE\">{{cite web |title=Levantamento do FGV IBRE aponta desigualdade recorde na renda do trabalho |url=https://portalibre.fgv.br/navegacao-superior/noticias/levantamento-do-fgv-ibre-aponta-desigualdade-recorde-na-renda-do-trabalho.htm |work=IBRE/FGV |accessdate=23 May 2019 |date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an Ibre researcher, Daniel Duque, the recovery of the job market benefited the  higher qualified and experienced most, reinforcing inequality. Many underqualified people gave up trying to get a job, and the loss of hope was at a \"[...] record high, and it helps to explain why, even after the decrease in unemployment, inequality kept rising.\"<ref name=\"Valor\" />\n\n=== Emigration ===\n{{main article|Brazilian diaspora}}\n[[File:Quantidade de declara\u00e7\u00f5es de sa\u00edda definitiva do Brasil.jpg|thumb|355px|Number of declarations of definite emigration from the country. Source:[[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=Cresce n\u00famero de brasileiros que decidem viver no exterior; pa\u00edses oferecem oportunidades de emprego|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/concursos-e-emprego/noticia/2019/04/03/cresce-numero-de-brasileiros-que-decidem-viver-no-exterior-paises-oferecem-oportunidades-de-emprego.ghtml|work=G1|author=Luiz Guilherme Gerbelli|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=3 April 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nThe number of declarations of definitive departure from the country began to grow in the first year of crisis and has increased steadily ever since, according to [[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]]. Among the countries that received the most Brazilian citizens were [[Japan]] and [[Canada]], which, due to low unemployment and aging populations among other reasons, needed a boost to decrease the age of the workforce.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAccording to a JBJ Partners employee (a company specialized in expatriation to the [[United States]]), many who fled Brazil were qualified workers:\n\n{{quote|We're talking about qualified people. The profile of the immigrant is no longer that of the poor individual looking for better opportunities. They are high executives, who are abandoning their careers to open a business abroad, people with Ph.D., which is sad because the country is losing resources.|Jorge Botrel, a JBJ partner.<ref>{{cite web |title=Com a crise, dispara a quantidade de brasileiros que desistem de viver no Brasil |url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/com-a-crise-dispara-a-quantidade-de-brasileiros-que-desistem-de-viver-no-brasil.ghtml |work=G1|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=17 December 2017|author=Lu\u00edsa Melo}}</ref>}}\n\nAn [[OECD]] report shows a much more elevated number<!-- In comparison to what? -->. In 2016 80,000 Brazilians emigrated legally to one of the member states of the OECD, whereas 99,000 did so in 2017. Similarly, data from Receita Federal shows that the number of people leaving Brazil increased in consecutive years since the beginning of the crisis.<ref>{{cite web |title=Imigra\u00e7\u00e3o de brasileiros para pa\u00edses da OCDE subiu 24%, o terceiro maior aumento |url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2019/09/18/politica/1568843366_553673.html |work=El Pa\u00eds|author=Felipe Betim|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Credit rating ===\nThis is a table of the credit ratings of the Brazilian economy according to Trading Economics.{{who|date=April 2017}}{{cn|date=April 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Agency !! Rating !! Outlook !! Date\n|-\n| Fitch || BB || negative || May 5, 2016\n|-\n| TE || 34 || negative || Apr 16 2016\n|-\n| Moody's || Ba2 || negative || Feb 24 2016\n|-\n| S&P || BB || negative || Feb 17 2016\n|}\n\n== Anti-crisis measures ==\n[[File:Entrevistas Diversas (30847431200).jpg|[[Henrique Meirelles]], the [[Ministry of Finance (Brazil)|Minister of Finance]] from May 2016 to April 2018.|thumb]]\nSince the impeachment of Dilma Rousseff and [[Michel Temer]]'s subsequent rise to power, several measures, most of which unpopular, were implemented or proposed to get the economy back on track.<ref>{{cite journal|title='Aproveito impopularidade para tomar medidas necess\u00e1rias', diz Temer|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2016/12/1843702-aproveito-impopularidade-para-tomar-medidas-necessarias-diz-temer.shtml|journal=Folha de S.Paulo|date=22 December 2016|accessdate=17 June 2017|author=Marina Dias Valdo Cruz|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref> The most important of which were:\n\n* The {{ill|95\u00ba Constitutional amendment|pt|Emenda Constitucional do Teto dos Gastos P\u00fablicos|vertical-align=sup}} (a.k.a \"new fiscal regime\"): Constitutional amendment which established a \"ceiling\" (upper limit) to government spending for the next 20 years;<ref>{{cite journal|title=Temer elogia aprova\u00e7\u00e3o da PEC do Teto e minimiza menor n\u00famero de votos a favor|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2016-12/temer-elogia-aprovacao-da-pec-do-teto-e-minimiza-menor-numero-de-votos|accessdate=17 June 2017|location=Bras\u00edlia|journal= Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=13 December 2016|author=Paulo Victor Chagas}}</ref>\n* The [[Outsourcing law in Brazil|Outsourcing law]], which allows companies to hire outsourced employees to work on primary activities, and not just secondary activities (such as security or cleaning);<ref>{{cite web|title=Com vetos, Temer sanciona lei que permite terceiriza\u00e7\u00e3o de atividade-fim|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-03/temer-sanciona-lei-que-permite-terceirizacao-em-atividade-fim-das-empresas|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=31 March 2017|author=Ivan Richard Esposito|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref>\n* The [[Brazil labor reform (2017)|2017 labor reform]], a significant change in the [[Consolidation of Labor Laws]]; and<ref>{{cite web|title=Com flexibiliza\u00e7\u00e3o de v\u00e1rios pontos da CLT, reforma trabalhista divide opini\u00f5es|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-04/com-flexibilizacao-de-varios-pontos-da-clt-reforma-trabalhista-divide|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|location=S\u00e3o Paulo|date=13 April 2017|author=Daniel Mello}}</ref>\n* a pension reform, which the government failed to approve.<ref>{{cite web|title=Governo desiste da vota\u00e7\u00e3o da Previd\u00eancia e anuncia nova pauta priorit\u00e1ria no Congresso|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/governo-desiste-da-votacao-da-previdencia-e-anuncia-nova-pauta-prioritaria-no-congresso.ghtml||work = G1|accessdate=26 May 2019|date=19 February 2018|author1=Guilherme Mazui |author2=Roniara Castilhos}}</ref>\n\nOne year after the labor reform was approved, however, it was verified that the decrease in unemployment was minimal, while the contracts of intermittent, outsourced and temporary labor increased.<ref>{{cite web|author=Fabiana Futema|date=10 November 2018|title=Um ano depois, reforma trabalhista n\u00e3o gera empregos esperados|url=https://veja.abril.com.br/economia/um-ano-depois-reforma-trabalhista-nao-gera-empregos-esperados/|work=VEJA.com|accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Recovery ==\nIn early 2017, there were already signals that the economy was beginning to recover, however, it was agreed that the process would be long and slow.<ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ser\u00e1 longa e lenta, aponta 'FT'|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-sera-longa-e-lenta-aponta-ft,70001658076}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ainda \u00e9 lenta, diz presidente do Ita\u00fa|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/mercado/2017/04/1876544-recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-ainda-e-lenta-diz-presidente-do-itau.shtml}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, a 1% rise in GDP in the first quarter of the year was reported.<ref name=\"jn\"/> It was the first rise of the GDP after eight consecutive falls (two years).<ref name=\":0\">\n{{Cite news|title= PIB do Brasil cresce 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre de 2017, ap\u00f3s 8 quedas seguidas|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-do-brasil-cresce-10-no-1-trimestre-de-2017.ghtml}}</ref> Minister of Finance [[Henrique Meirelles]] said that the country had left the \"greatest recession of the century.\"<ref>{{citation |title=PIB sobe 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre, ap\u00f3s oito quedas consecutivas|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,pib-sobe-1-0-no-1-trimestre-apos-oito-quedas-consecutivas,70001821658}}</ref> However, economists say that the growth characterizes only the end of the \"technical recession\" and that it is still too early to claim that the crisis is over, given that unemployment remains high and there's still widespread uncertainty regarding the future of the economy, especially in the aftermath of the recent political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Comparisons with other crises ==\n[[Image:Countries_by_Real_GDP_Growth_Rate_(2016).svg|thumb|Real GDP growth in 2016. Source:''CIA World Factbook''<ref>{{cite web|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2003rank.html|work=Central Intelligence Agency (CIA)}}</ref>|355px]]\nIn countries with similar size and wealth, there were a few, but less severe crisis in the same period. In 2015, among [[OECD]] countries, only [[Russia]] went through a recession. Even after the economic sanctions imposed by other countries due to the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|conflict in Ukraine]], Russia's GDP fell by only 4% in two years (2015 and 2016). Few other countries in this period were going through a recession, which reinforces the argument that the crisis in Brazil was mainly due to local causes.<ref name=\"book\">{{Cite book|last=Carvalho|first=Laura|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XppWDwAAQBAJ|title=Valsa brasileira: Do boom ao caos econ\u00f4mico|date=2018-05-08|publisher=Editora Todavia S.A|isbn=978-85-93828-63-8|language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n\nIn comparison to other crises in Brazil, it was verified that the 2014 crisis was not the deepest, as previously thought. After the GDP values for 2015 and 2016 were reviewed by the [[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics]] (IBGE), the economy shrank by 8.2% in the period, in contrast to the 8.5% in the 1981 recession. Despite not being the deepest, the crisis was long. It was also followed by the slowest recovery of all.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nAccording to Codace (committee part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]]), the 1981 crisis lasted nine trimesters, reached its peak in the first trimester of 1983 and, since then, took seven trimesters for the GDP the reach its pre-crisis level. Later, the 1989-1992 crisis lasted 11 trimesters and the recovery time was the same: seven trimesters. This crisis, however, had a lower intensity, with an accumulated decrease in the GDP of 7.7%.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nIn turn, the GDP after the 2014 crisis will only reach its pre-crisis level in 2022, according to an optimistic estimate, with 20 trimesters of recovery in total. When taking into account not only the GDP, but also the employment rate, the recovery will be even slower. In addition to the sluggish recovery, the new jobs will be of lower quality, including informal and autonomous labor.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Brazil labor reform (2017)]]\n* [[Economy of Brazil]]\n* [[2018 in Brazil]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Government of Michel Temer}}\n{{Financial crises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2014 Brazilian economic recession}}\n[[Category:2010s economic history]]\n[[Category:2014 in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Economic crises in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Recessions]]\n[[Category:Government of Michel Temer]]\n[[Category:Economic history of Brazil]]\n", "name_user": "20182309L", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014_Brazilian_economic_crisis"}
{"title_page": "OpenMandriva Lx", "text_new": "{{Infobox OS\n| name = OpenMandriva Lx\n| logo = Oma-logo-22042013 300pp.png\n| logo_size = x70px\n| screenshot = File:Openmandriva.png\n| caption = OpenMandriva Lx 4.0 Einsteinium with KDE Plasma 5 interface\n| developer = OpenMandriva Association and Cooker group\n| family = [[Unix-like]] (originally based on [[Mandriva Linux]])\n| working_state = Current\n| source_model = [[Open-source software|Open source]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/OpenMandrivaAssociation/|title=OpenMandriva Association|website=GitHub|language=en|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n| released = {{Start date and age|2013|11|22}}\n| latest release version = Lx 4.1<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.openmandriva.org/en/news/article/and-openmandriva-did-better-omlx-4-1-final-release-is-out-now|title=OMLx 4.1 final release is out now!|date=2020-02-01|access-date=2020-02-09|}}</ref>\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2020|02|01}}\n| latest preview version =\n| latest preview date = <--{{Start date and age|2019|11|10}}-->\n| updatemodel = dnf (command line) and dnfdragora (GUI)\n| package_manager = [[RPM Package Manager#RPM.org|RPM.org]] (RPMv4)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forum.openmandriva.org/t/switching-to-rpmv4/1702|title=Switching to RPMv4|publisher=OMA Forum|accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"openmandrivalx4.0a1\" />\n| supported_platforms = [[IA-32]], [[x86-64]], [[i586]], [[ARM architecture|ARM]], [[ARM architecture|ARMv8-A]]\n| kernel_type = [[Monolithic kernel|Monolithic]] ([[Linux kernel|Linux]])\n| userland = [[GNU Core Utilities|GNU]]\n| ui = [[KDE Plasma 5]], [[KDE Plasma 4]], [[LXQt]]\n| license = [[Free software]] (mainly [[GPL]])\n}}\n'''OpenMandriva Lx''' is a [[Linux distribution]] forked from [[Mandriva Linux]].  It is published by the OpenMandriva Association.\n\n== History ==\n===Origin of the distribution===\nOpenMandriva Lx is a community [[Linux]] distribution. Originally an offering of [[Mandriva Linux]], the OpenMandriva product was created in May, 2012, when [[Mandriva|Mandriva S.A.]] avoided bankruptcy by abandoning the development of its consumer product to the Mandriva community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.mandriva.com/en/2012/05/17/mandriva-linux-will-return-to-the-community/ |url-status=dead |title=Mandriva SA official blog: Mandriva Linux will return to the community |date=17 May 2012 |accessdate=2015-12-13 |publisher=[[Mandriva]] |archive-date=2015-05-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150523070604/https://blog.mandriva.com/en/2012/05/17/mandriva-linux-will-return-to-the-community/ }}</ref><ref>[https://distrowatch.com/weekly.php?issue=20121217#news DistroWatch Weekly, Issue 487, 17 December 2012]</ref> The first stable version (OpenMandriva Lx 2013 \"Oxygen\") was released in late 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://distrowatch.com/8172|title=Distribution Release: OpenMandriva Lx 2013.0 )|first=|last=|publisher=DistroWatch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ostatic.com/blog/first-community-openmandriva-released|title=First Community OpenMandriva Released|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423050211/http://ostatic.com/blog/first-community-openmandriva-released|archivedate=2014-04-23}}</ref>\n\n===OpenMandriva Association===\nThe OpenMandriva Association was established on December 12, 2012 under [[:fr:Loi 1901|1901 French law]], to represent the OpenMandriva Community.<ref>[https://www.openmandriva.org/en/documentation/association/About?q=%2Fabout About - OpenMandriva]</ref> It manages free software projects including OpenMandriva Lx.\n\n=== OpenMandriva Lx development environment ===\nOpenMandriva Lx's development environment is an ABF (Automated Build Farm) which can manage the source codes, compile it to binaries. Also ABF creates the package repository and ISO images.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.openmandriva.org/2016/04/brand-new-openmandriva-development-environment-abf|title=Brand new OpenMandriva development environment \u2013 ABF! \u2013 OMA blog|website=blog.openmandriva.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://distrowatch.com/dwres.php?resource=showheadline&story=250|title=OpenMandriva opens build farm|last=DistroWatch|website=distrowatch.com|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n\n==Versions==\nIn late 2013, the first version of OpenMandriva Lx was released. It was based on Mandriva Linux 2011, which was itself an amalgamation of [[ROSA Linux]] and Mandriva SA.<ref name=\"distrowatch1\">{{cite web|url=http://distrowatch.com/weekly.php?issue=20131209#feature|title=DistroWatch Weekly|first=|last=|publisher=DistroWatch}}</ref><ref name=\"linuxbsdos1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.linuxbsdos.com/2013/11/30/openmandriva-lx-2013-0-review/|title=OpenMandriva Lx 2013.0 review - LinuxBSDos.com|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"mylinuxexplore1\">{{cite web|url=http://mylinuxexplore.blogspot.fr/2013/11/openmandriva-lx-20130-review-looks.html|title=Linuxed - Exploring Linux distros: OpenMandriva Lx 2013.0 Review: Looks awesome but needs to improve functionality and performance|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"navychristian1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.navychristian.org/2013/11/openmandriva-lx-20130-review.html|title=The Navy Christian: OpenMandriva Lx 2013.0 Review|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOpenMandriva Lx 2014 \"Phosphorus\" was released on 1 May 2014.<ref name=\"blogopenmandriva20140\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.openmandriva.org/en/2014/05/a-breath-of-fresh-air-with-a-kde-soul-openmandriva%C2%AD-lx-2014-is-burning-free/|title=\u201cA Breath of Fresh Air with a KDE Soul\u201d* \u2013 OpenMandriva Lx 2014 is burning free! |publisher= OpenMandriva Association}}</ref><ref name=\"distrowatch2\">{{cite web|url=http://distrowatch.com/weekly.php?issue=20140602#feature|title=DistroWatch Weekly|first=|last=|publisher=DistroWatch}}</ref><ref name=\"dasublog\">{{cite web|url=http://dasublogbyprashanth.blogspot.fr/2014/05/review-openmandriva-lx-20140.html|title=Das U-Blog by Prashanth: Review: OpenMandriva Lx 2014.0|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"hectic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hecticgeek.com/2014/05/openmandriva-lx-2014-0-review/|title='OpenMandriva Lx 2014.0' Review - Slow to Boot, High Memory Consumption, But Responsive & Easy to Configure|date=4 May 2014|publisher=}}</ref> The release had a very positive review from one of the founders of the initial [[Mandrake Linux]] distribution, [[Ga\u00ebl Duval]].<ref name=\"duval\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indidea.org/gael/blog/?p=444|title=A quick tour of OpenMandriva Lx 2014.0 (Phosphorus)}}</ref>\n\nOpenMandriva Lx 2014.2, codenamed \"The Scion\", a bugfix release for 2014.1, was released on 29 June 2015.<ref name=\"blogopenmandriva20142\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.openmandriva.org/2015/06/the-scion-is-ready/|title=The Scion is ready! \u00bb OMA blog|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"blogopenmandrivatribute\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.openmandriva.org/en/2015/05/tribute-to-mandrake/|title=Tribute to Mandrake \u00bb OMA blog|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"distrowatch3\">{{cite web|url=http://distrowatch.com/8997|title=Distribution Release: OpenMandriva Lx 2014.2|first=|last=|publisher=DistroWatch}}</ref><ref name=\"softpedia1\">{{cite web|url=http://news.softpedia.com/news/openmandriva-lx-2014-2-officially-released-as-a-tribute-to-mandrake-linux-485733.shtml|title=OpenMandriva Lx 2014.2 Officially Released as a Tribute to Mandrake Linux|first=Marius|last=Nestor|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"phoronix1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.phoronix.com/scan.php?page=news_item&px=OpenMandriva-Lx-2014.2|title=OpenMandriva Lx 2014.2 \"The Scion\" Pays Tribute To Mandrake |publisher=Phoronix}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2015, OpenMandriva released an alpha version of OpenMandriva Lx 2015. As the operating system was developed all 2015 year, in 2016, the version was released as OpenMandriva Lx 3.0 Beta.<ref name=\"blogopenmandriva30beta\">[https://blog.openmandriva.org/2016/06/openmandriva-lx-3-0-beta2-is-here/ OpenMandriva Lx 3.0 Beta 2 is here! - OMA blog]</ref> This new release came with significant changes to the core system \u2014 among other things, it was the first desktop Linux distribution that was built completely with the [[Clang]] compiler instead of GCC.<ref>[https://distrowatch.com/dwres.php?resource=showheadline&story=463 OpenMandriva uses Clang], '''DistroWatch'''</ref>\n\nA stable and final release of OpenMandriva Lx 3.0 was released in August 2016,<ref name=\"blogopenmandriva30\">{{Cite web|url=https://blog.openmandriva.org/2016/08/openmandriva-lx-3-0-final-release-is-out/|title=OpenMandriva Lx 3.0 Final Release is out! \u2013 OMA blog|website=blog.openmandriva.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref><ref name=\"dwweekly2016\">[https://distrowatch.com/weekly.php?issue=20160919#openmandriva DistroWatch Weekly, Issue 679, 19 September 2016]</ref> followed by 3.01 in December 2016<ref name=\"blogopenmandriva301\">[https://blog.openmandriva.org/2016/12/openmandriva-lx-3-01-our-holidays-gift/ OpenMandriva Lx 3.01 - our holidays gift - OMA blog]</ref><ref name=\"linuxbsdos301\">[http://linuxbsdos.com/2017/01/02/openmandriva-lx-3-01-review/ OpenMandriva Lx 3.01 review | LinuxBSDos.com]</ref> and 3.02 in June 2017.<ref name=\"openmandriva302\">[https://www.openmandriva.org/en/news/article/a-proud-scion-of-name-openmandriva-lx-3-02-release/ A proud scion of name: OpenMandriva Lx 3.02 release - OpenMandriva]</ref> This was followed by OpenMandriva Lx 3.03, which was released in November 2017.<ref name=\"openmandriva303\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.openmandriva.org/en/news/article/openmandriva-lx-3-03-get-it-while-it-s-hot|title=OpenMandriva Lx 3.03 - Get it while it\u2019s hot! - OpenMandriva|website=www.openmandriva.org|language=en|access-date=2017-11-23}}</ref><ref name=\"distrowatch303\">[https://distrowatch.com/?newsid=10036 Distribution Release: OpenMandriva Lx 3.03 (DistroWatch.com News)]</ref>\n\nAfter releasing OpenMandriva Lx 3.03, OpenMandriva Lx developers started dropping support of i586 processor architecture in OpenMandriva Lx 4.0.<ref name=\"openmandriva303\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phoronix.com/scan.php?page=news_item&px=OpenMandriva-Dropping-32-bit|title=OpenMandriva Is Going To Do Away With 32-bit Support - Phoronix|website=www.phoronix.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n\nThe development of OpenMandriva Lx 4.0 continued on for two years after Lx 3.03 was released.<ref name=\"openmandrivaplans40\">[https://www.openmandriva.org/en/news/article/openmandriva-upcoming-release-plans-for-lx-3-03-and-lx-4-0 OpenMandriva upcoming release plans for Lx 3.03 and Lx 4.0 \u2014 OpenMandriva]</ref><ref name=\"40wiki\">[https://wiki.openmandriva.org/en/4.0 4.0 \u2014 Wiki en OpenMandriva]</ref><ref name=\"phoronix40\">[https://www.phoronix.com/scan.php?page=news_item&px=OpenMandriva-Lx-4.0-Prepping OpenMandriva 4.0 Being Prepared With zSTD-Enabled Linux 4.16, Clang Pre-7.0, GCC 8 - Phoronix]</ref><ref name=\"softp40\">[https://news.softpedia.com/news/openmandriva-lx-4-0-planned-linux-kernel-4-12-coming-to-openmandriva-lx-3-users-516890.shtml OpenMandriva Lx 4.0 Planned, Linux Kernel 4.12 Comes to OpenMandriva Lx 3 Users], '''Softpedia News'''</ref><ref name=\"summer2018\">[https://www.openmandriva.org/en/news/article/summer-news Summer news - OpenMandriva]</ref><ref name=\"201828dev\">[https://www.openmandriva.org/en/news/article/development-news-week-2018-28 Development news Week 2018-28 - OpenMandriva]</ref><ref name=\"softp240\">[https://news.softpedia.com/news/openmandriva-lx-4-launching-soon-with-kde-plasma-5-13-gcc-8-1-and-linux-4-18-521867.shtml OpenMandriva Lx 4 Launching Soon with KDE Plasma 5.13, GCC 8.1, and Linux 4.18], '''Softpedia News'''</ref><ref name=\"phoronix240\">[https://www.phoronix.com/scan.php?page=news_item&px=OpenMandriva-LX4-Approaching OpenMandriva Lx 4.0 Is Approaching With DNF/RPM4, KDE Plasma 5.13, Linux 4.17~4.18 - Phoronix]</ref>\n\nThe OpenMandriva Lx 4.0 stable release arrived in June 2019.<ref name=\"blogopenmandriva40\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.openmandriva.org/en/news/article/the-best-until-openmandriva-does-better-released-omlx-4-0|title=The best, until OpenMandriva does better: released OMLx 4.0 - OpenMandriva|website=www.openmandriva.org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-23}}</ref> Among many other changes, this release is notable for switching to the [[DNF_(software)|DNF package manager]] for software management<ref name=\"omv4urpm2dnf\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.openmandriva.org/en/4.0/Release_Notes#Package_Management_.28change_from_URPMI_to_DNF.29|title=4.0/Release Notes - Wiki [en] OpenMandriva|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-23}}</ref>, including [[Mageia]]'s dnfdragora to replace rpmdrake.<ref name=\"openmandrivalx4beta\" />\n\n=== Version history ===\n<!-- Template:Version - for version & release history. Documentation and examples: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Version -->\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-left:1em; margin-right:0\"\n|-\n! Version !! Code name<ref name=\"release-list\" /> !! Release date<ref name=\"release-list\">https://wiki.openmandriva.org/en/Category:Releases</ref>!! End-of-life date !! Kernel version\n|-\n| {{Version |o |2013.0}}\n| Oxygen\n| 2013-11-22\n| 2014-05-28<ref>[https://blog.openmandriva.org/2014/07/openmandriva-2013-0-lx-end-of-life/ OpenMandriva 2013.0 Lx End of Life &#8211; OMA blog]</ref>\n| 3.11.8\n|-\n| {{Version |o |2014.0}}\n| Phosphorus\n| 2014-05-09\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2017-11-21\n| 3.13.11\n|-\n| {{Version |o |2014.1}}\n| Phosphorus\n| 2014-10-26\n| 3.15.10\n|-\n| {{Version |o |2014.2}}\n| The Scion\n| 2015-06-29\n| 3.18.12\n|-\n| {{Version |co |3.0}}\n| Einsteinium\n| 2016-08-14\n| rowspan=\"6\" {{TBA}}\n| 4.6.5\n|-\n| {{Version |co |3.01}}\n| Einsteinium\n| 2016-12-25\n| 4.9.0\n|-\n| {{Version |co |3.02}}\n| Einsteinium\n| 2017-06-21\n| 4.11.3\n|-\n| {{Version |co |3.03}}\n| Einsteinium\n| 2017-11-21\n| 4.13.12\n|-\n|-\n|